{"title_page": "Ebola vaccine", "text_new": "{{short description|Any of several vaccines to prevent Ebola}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox drug\n| drug_name         = \n| type              = vaccine\n| image             = Study Participant Receives NIAID-GSK Candidate Ebola Vaccine (3).jpg\n| caption           = Candidate ''Ebola vaccine'' being given\n| alt               = \n| width             = \n| image2            = \n| alt2              = \n| width2            = \n| target            = [[Zaire ebolavirus|Ebola virus]]\n| vaccine_type      = attenuated\n<!-- Clinical data -->\n| pronounce         = \n| tradename         = Ervebo\n| Drugs.com         = \n| MedlinePlus       = \n| licence_CA        = <!-- Health Canada may use generic or brand name (generic name preferred) -->\n| licence_EU        = <!-- EMA uses INN (or special INN_EMA) -->\n| DailyMedID        = <!-- DailyMed may use generic or brand name (generic name preferred) -->\n| licence_US        = Ervebo\n| pregnancy_AU      = <!-- A/B1/B2/B3/C/D/X -->\n| pregnancy_US      = <!-- A/B/C/D/X -->\n| pregnancy_category= \n| legal_AU = <!-- S2, S3, S4, S5, S6, S7, S8, S9 or Unscheduled -->\n| legal_BR =  <!-- OTC, A1, A2, A3, B1, B2, C1, C2, C3, C4, C5, D1, D2, E, F -->\n| legal_CA = <!-- OTC, Rx-only, Schedule I, II, III, IV, V, VI, VII, VIII -->\n| legal_UK = <!-- GSL, P, POM, CD, CD Lic, CD POM, CD No Reg POM, CD (Benz) POM, CD (Anab) POM or CD Inv POM -->\n| legal_US = Rx-only\n| legal_UN = <!-- N I, II, III, IV / P I, II, III, IV -->\n| legal_NZ = <!-- Class A, B, C -->\n| legal_status      = \n| dependency_liability = \n| addiction_liability = \n| routes_of_administration = \n<!-- Identifiers -->\n| CAS_number        = \n| CAS_supplemental  = \n| ATCvet            = \n| ATC_prefix        = J07\n| ATC_suffix        = BX02\n| ATC_supplemental  = \n| PubChem           = \n| PubChemSubstance  = \n| IUPHAR_ligand     = \n| DrugBank          = \n| ChemSpiderID      = \n| UNII              = \n| KEGG              = \n| ChEBI             = \n| ChEMBL            = \n| NIAID_ChemDB      = \n}}\n\n'''Ebola vaccines''' are a number of [[vaccines]] to prevent [[Ebola virus disease|Ebola]] that are either approved or in development. The first vaccine to be approved in the United States was [[rVSV-ZEBOV]] in December 2019.<ref name=\"FDA PR\">{{cite web | title=First FDA-approved vaccine for the prevention of Ebola virus disease, marking a critical milestone in public health preparedness and response | website=U.S. [[Food and Drug Administration]] (FDA) | date=19 December 2019 | url=https://www.fda.gov/news-events/press-announcements/first-fda-approved-vaccine-prevention-ebola-virus-disease-marking-critical-milestone-public-health | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191220052152/https://www.fda.gov/news-events/press-announcements/first-fda-approved-vaccine-prevention-ebola-virus-disease-marking-critical-milestone-public-health | archive-date=20 December 2019 | url-status=live | access-date=19 December 2019}} {{PD-notice}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.pharmatimes.com/news/us_approves_mercks_ebola_vaccine_1320832|title=US approves Merck's Ebola vaccine|last=McKee|first=Selina | name-list-format = vanc |date=23 December 2019|work=PharmaTimes Online|access-date=24 Dec 2019|url-status=live|publisher=PharmaTimes Media Limited|location=Surrey, England}}</ref>  It had been used extensively in [[DRC Ebola epidemic 2018-19|2018\u201319]] under  a [[compassionate use]] protocol.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://arstechnica.com/science/2019/04/ebola-vaccine-is-97-5-effective-early-outbreak-data-suggests/ |title = As Ebola outbreak rages, vaccine is 97.5% effective, protecting over 90K people|date = 2019-04-16}}</ref> Several promising vaccine candidates have been shown to protect nonhuman primates (usually [[macaques]]) against lethal infection.<ref name=\"Hoenen2012\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Hoenen T, Groseth A, Feldmann H | title = Current ebola vaccines | journal = Expert Opinion on Biological Therapy | volume = 12 | issue = 7 | pages = 859\u201372 | date = July 2012 | pmid = 22559078 | pmc = 3422127 | doi = 10.1517/14712598.2012.685152 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Peterson AT, Bauer JT, Mills JN | title = Ecologic and geographic distribution of filovirus disease | journal = Emerging Infectious Diseases | volume = 10 | issue = 1 | pages = 40\u201347 | date = January 2004 | pmid = 15078595 | pmc = 3322747 | doi = 10.3201/eid1001.030125 }}</ref><ref name=\"Hugues2012\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Fausther-Bovendo H, Mulangu S, Sullivan NJ | title = Ebolavirus vaccines for humans and apes | journal = Current Opinion in Virology | volume = 2 | issue = 3 | pages = 324\u201329 | date = June 2012 | pmid = 22560007 | pmc = 3397659 | doi = 10.1016/j.coviro.2012.04.003 }}</ref>\n\nVaccines include [[viral replication|replication]]-deficient [[adenovirus]] vectors, replication-competent [[vesicular stomatitis]] (VSV) and [[Human parainfluenza viruses|human parainfluenza]] (HPIV-3) vectors, and virus-like [[nanoparticle]] preparations. Conventional trials to study efficacy by exposure of humans to the pathogen after immunization are not ethical in this case. For such situations, the [[Food and Drug Administration]] (FDA) has established the \"[[animal efficacy rule]]\" allowing licensure to be approved on the basis of [[animal model]] studies that replicate human disease, combined with evidence of safety and a potentially potent [[immune response]] (antibodies in the blood) from humans given the vaccine. [[Phases of clinical research|Clinical trials]] involve the administration of the vaccine to healthy human subjects to evaluate the immune response, identify any side effects and determine the appropriate dosage.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Pavot V | title = Ebola virus vaccines: Where do we stand? | journal = Clinical Immunology | volume = 173 | pages = 44\u201349 | date = December 2016 | pmid = 27910805 | doi = 10.1016/j.clim.2016.10.016 }}</ref>\n\n==Approved==\n=== rVSV-ZEBOV ===\n{{details|rVSV-ZEBOV}}\n\nVSV-EBOV or [[rVSV-ZEBOV]], sold under the brand name Ervebo, is a vaccine based on the [[vesicular stomatitis]] virus which was genetically modified to express a surface glycoprotein of Zaire Ebola virus.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Marzi A, Hanley PW, Haddock E, Martellaro C, Kobinger G, Feldmann H | title = Efficacy of Vesicular Stomatitis Virus-Ebola Virus Postexposure Treatment in Rhesus Macaques Infected With Ebola Virus Makona | journal = The Journal of Infectious Diseases | volume = 214 | issue = suppl 3 | pages = S360\u201366 | date = October 2016 | pmid = 27496978 | pmc = 5050468 | doi = 10.1093/infdis/jiw218 | url = https://academic.oup.com/jid/article-pdf/214/suppl_3/S360/7935990/jiw218.pdf }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Marzi A, Robertson SJ, Haddock E, Feldmann F, Hanley PW, Scott DP, Strong JE, Kobinger G, Best SM, Feldmann H | display-authors = 6 | title = Ebola Vaccine. VSV-EBOV rapidly protects macaques against infection with the 2014/15 Ebola virus outbreak strain | journal = Science | volume = 349 | issue = 6249 | pages = 739\u201342 | date = August 2015 | pmid = 26249231 | doi = 10.1126/science.aab3920 }}</ref> In November 2019, the European Commission granted a conditional marketing authorization.<ref>{{cite press release | title=Merck's Ervebo [Ebola Zaire Vaccine (rVSV\u0394G-ZEBOV-GP) live] Granted Conditional Approval in the European Union | publisher=Merck | via=Business Wire | date=11 November 2019 | url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20191111005601/en/Merck%E2%80%99s-ERVEBO%C2%AE-Ebola-Zaire-Vaccine-rVSV%CE%94G-ZEBOV-GP-live | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191111221058/https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20191111005601/en/Merck%E2%80%99s-ERVEBO%C2%AE-Ebola-Zaire-Vaccine-rVSV%CE%94G-ZEBOV-GP-live | archive-date=11 November 2019 | url-status=live | access-date=11 November 2019}}</ref> The WHO prequalification came fewer than 48 hours later, making it the fastest vaccine prequalification process ever conducted by WHO.<ref name=\":1\" /> In December 2019 it was approved for medical use in the United States.<ref name=\"FDA PR\" />\n\nIt was developed by the [[Public Health Agency of Canada]], with development subsequently taken over by [[Merck & Co.|Merck Inc]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/health/canadian-ebola-vaccine-development-taken-over-by-merck-1.2847128|title=Canadian Ebola vaccine development taken over by Merck|date=24 November 2014|publisher=[[CBC News]]|access-date=25 November 2014}}</ref> In October 2014, the [[Wellcome Trust]], who was also one of the biggest UK founders,<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Henao-Restrepo AM, Longini IM, Egger M, Dean NE, Edmunds WJ, Camacho A, Carroll MW, Doumbia M, Draguez B, Duraffour S, Enwere G, Grais R, Gunther S, Hossmann S, Kond\u00e9 MK, Kone S, Kuisma E, Levine MM, Mandal S, Norheim G, Riveros X, Soumah A, Trelle S, Vicari AS, Watson CH, K\u00e9\u00efta S, Kieny MP, R\u00f8ttingen JA | display-authors = 6 | title = Efficacy and effectiveness of an rVSV-vectored vaccine expressing Ebola surface glycoprotein: interim results from the Guinea ring vaccination cluster-randomised trial | journal = Lancet | volume = 386 | issue = 9996 | pages = 857\u201366 | date = August 2015 | pmid = 26248676 | doi = 10.1016/s0140-6736(15)61117-5 | hdl = 10144/575218 }}</ref> announced the start of multiple trials in healthy volunteers in Europe, Gabon, Kenya, and the US.<ref>{{cite press release |title=Multiple trials of VSV Ebola vaccine accelerated by international collaborative|url=http://www.wellcome.ac.uk/News/Media-office/Press-releases/2014/WTP057790.htm|publisher=Wellcome Trust|access-date=29 October 2014}}</ref> The vaccine was proven safe at multiple sites in North America, Europe, and Africa, but several volunteers at one trial site in Geneva, Switzerland, developed vaccine-related arthritis after about two weeks, and about 20\u201330% of volunteers at reporting sites developed low-grade post-vaccine fever, which resolved within a day or two. Other common side-effects were pain at the site of injection, myalgia, and fatigue.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Shuchman M | title = Ebola vaccine trial in west Africa faces criticism | journal = Lancet | volume = 385 | issue = 9981 | pages = 1933\u201334 | date = May 2015 | pmid = 25979835 | doi = 10.1016/s0140-6736(15)60938-2 }}</ref> The trial was temporarily halted in December 2014 due to possible adverse effects, but subsequently resumed.<ref>{{cite web |first1= Margaret |last1=Chan | name-list-format = vanc |authorlink1=Margaret Chan |title=WHO Director-General opens high-level meeting on Ebola vaccines|url=http://www.who.int/dg/speeches/2015/ebola-vaccines-meeting/en/|publisher=[[World Health Organization]] (WHO)|access-date=10 January 2015}}</ref> {{As of|April 2015}}, a Phase III trial with a single dose of VSV-EBOV began in Liberia after a successful Phase II study in the West African country.<ref name=\"NIHPR\"/> On 31 July 2015, preliminary results of a Phase III trial in Guinea indicated that the vaccine appears to be \"highly efficacious and safe.\"<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Henao-Restrepo AM, Longini IM, Egger M, Dean NE, Edmunds WJ, Camacho A, Carroll MW, Doumbia M, Draguez B, Duraffour S, Enwere G, Grais R, Gunther S, Hossmann S, Kond\u00e9 MK, Kone S, Kuisma E, Levine MM, Mandal S, Norheim G, Riveros X, Soumah A, Trelle S, Vicari AS, Watson CH, K\u00e9\u00efta S, Kieny MP, R\u00f8ttingen JA | display-authors = 6 | title = Efficacy and effectiveness of an rVSV-vectored vaccine expressing Ebola surface glycoprotein: interim results from the Guinea ring vaccination cluster-randomised trial | journal = Lancet | volume = 386 | issue = 9996 | pages = 857\u201366 | date = August 2015 | pmid = 26248676 | doi = 10.1016/S0140-6736(15)61117-5 | hdl = 10144/575218 }}</ref> The trial used a [[ring vaccination]] protocol that first vaccinated all the closest contacts of new cases of Ebola infection either immediately or after 21 days. Because of the demonstrated efficacy of immediate vaccination, all recipients will now be immunized immediately.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ebola update (93): Positive vaccine trial results |url=http://www.promedmail.org/direct.php?id=3552116|website=ProMED mail|publisher=International Society for Infectious Diseases|access-date=2 August 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"who.int\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.who.int/features/2016/ebola-contacts-vaccination/en/|title=WHO coordinating vaccination of contacts to contain Ebola flare-up in Guinea|date=March 2016|publisher=[[World Health Organization]] (WHO)|access-date=2016-05-14}}</ref> Ring vaccination is the method used in the program to eradicate [[smallpox]] in the 1970s. The trial will continue to assess whether the vaccine is effective in creating [[herd immunity]] to Ebola virus infection.<ref>{{cite press release|title=World on the verge of an effective Ebola vaccine|url=http://who.int/mediacentre/news/releases/2015/effective-ebola-vaccine/en/|publisher=[[World Health Organization]] (WHO)|date=31 July 2015}}</ref> In December 2016, a study found the VSV-EBOV vaccine to be 95\u2013100% effective against the Ebola virus, making it the first proven vaccine against the disease.<ref name=\"TL-20161222\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Henao-Restrepo AM, Camacho A, Longini IM, Watson CH, Edmunds WJ, Egger M, Carroll MW, Dean NE, Diatta I, Doumbia M, Draguez B, Duraffour S, Enwere G, Grais R, Gunther S, Gsell PS, Hossmann S, Watle SV, Kond\u00e9 MK, K\u00e9\u00efta S, Kone S, Kuisma E, Levine MM, Mandal S, Mauget T, Norheim G, Riveros X, Soumah A, Trelle S, Vicari AS, R\u00f8ttingen JA, Kieny MP | display-authors = 6 | title = Efficacy and effectiveness of an rVSV-vectored vaccine in preventing Ebola virus disease: final results from the Guinea ring vaccination, open-label, cluster-randomised trial (Ebola \u00c7a Suffit!) | journal = Lancet | volume = 389 | issue = 10068 | pages = 505\u201318 | date = February 2017 | pmid = 28017403 | pmc = 5364328 | doi = 10.1016/S0140-6736(16)32621-6 }}</ref><ref name=\"CNN-2016122\">{{cite news |last=Berlinger |first=Joshua | name-list-format = vanc |title=Ebola vaccine gives 100% protection, study finds |url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/12/22/health/ebola-vaccine-study/index.html |date=22 December 2016 |publisher=[[CNN]] |access-date=27 December 2016 }}</ref><ref name=\"WHO 23-12-2016\">{{cite press release | title=Final trial results confirm Ebola vaccine provides high protection against disease | website=[[World Health Organization]] (WHO) | date=23 December 2016 | url=https://www.who.int/en/news-room/detail/23-12-2016-final-trial-results-confirm-ebola-vaccine-provides-high-protection-against-disease | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191111230728/https://www.who.int/en/news-room/detail/23-12-2016-final-trial-results-confirm-ebola-vaccine-provides-high-protection-against-disease | archive-date=11 November 2019 | url-status=live | access-date=11 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe approval was supported by a study conducted in Guinea during the 2014\u20132016 outbreak in individuals 18 years of age and older.<ref name=\"FDA PR\" /> The study was a randomized cluster (ring) vaccination study in which 3,537 contacts, and contacts of contacts, of individuals with laboratory-confirmed Ebola virus disease (EVD) received either \"immediate\" or 21-day \"delayed\" vaccination.<ref name=\"FDA PR\" /> This noteworthy design was intended to capture a social network of individuals and locations that might include dwellings or workplaces where a patient spent time while symptomatic, or the households of individuals who had contact with the patient during that person's illness or death.<ref name=\"FDA PR\" /> In a comparison of cases of EVD among 2,108 individuals in the \"immediate\" vaccination arm and 1,429 individuals in the \"delayed\" vaccination arm, Ervebo was determined to be 100% effective in preventing Ebola cases with symptom onset greater than ten days after vaccination.<ref name=\"FDA PR\" /> No cases of EVD with symptom onset greater than ten days after vaccination were observed in the \"immediate\" cluster group, compared with ten cases of EVD in the 21-day \"delayed\" cluster group.<ref name=\"FDA PR\" />\n\nIn additional studies, antibody responses were assessed in 477 individuals in Liberia, approximately 500 individuals in Sierra Leone and approximately 900 individuals in Canada, Spain and the U.S.<ref name=\"FDA PR\" /> The antibody responses among those in the study conducted in Canada, Spain and the U.S. were similar to those among individuals in the studies conducted in Liberia and Sierra Leone.<ref name=\"FDA PR\" /> \n\nThe safety was assessed in approximately 15,000 individuals in Africa, Europe and North America.<ref name=\"FDA PR\" /> The most commonly reported side effects were pain, swelling and redness at the injection site, as well as headache, fever, joint and muscle aches and fatigue.<ref name=\"FDA PR\" />\n\nIn December 2016, a study found the [[VSV-EBOV]] vaccine to be 70\u2013100% effective against the Ebola virus, making it the first proven vaccine against the disease.<ref name=\"TL-20161222\" /><ref name=\"CNN-2016122\" /><ref name=\"WHO 23-12-2016\" /> However, the design of this study and the high efficacy of the vaccine were questioned.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Metzger WG, Vivas-Mart\u00ednez S | title = Questionable efficacy of the rVSV-ZEBOV Ebola vaccine | journal = Lancet | volume = 391 | issue = 10125 | pages = 1021 | date = March 2018 | pmid = 29565013 | doi = 10.1016/S0140-6736(18)30560-9 }}</ref> In November 2019, the European Commission granted a conditional marketing authorization to Ervebo (Ebola Zaire Vaccine (rVSV\u2206G-ZEBOV-GP, live))<ref name=\"Merck PR\">{{cite press release | title=Merck's Ervebo [Ebola Zaire Vaccine (rVSV\u0394G-ZEBOV-GP) live] Granted Conditional Approval in the European Union | publisher=Merck | via=Business Wire | date=November 11, 2019 | url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20191111005601/en/Merck%E2%80%99s-ERVEBO%C2%AE-Ebola-Zaire-Vaccine-rVSV%CE%94G-ZEBOV-GP-live | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191111221058/https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20191111005601/en/Merck%E2%80%99s-ERVEBO%C2%AE-Ebola-Zaire-Vaccine-rVSV%CE%94G-ZEBOV-GP-live | archive-date=November 11, 2019 | url-status=live | access-date=November 11, 2019}}</ref> and the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) prequalified an Ebola vaccine for the first time.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite press release|url=https://www.who.int/news-room/detail/12-11-2019-who-prequalifies-ebola-vaccine-paving-the-way-for-its-use-in-high-risk-countries|title=WHO prequalifies Ebola vaccine, paving the way for its use in high-risk countries|website=[[World Health Organization]] (WHO)|date=November 12, 2019|access-date=2019-11-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191115045218/https://www.who.int/news-room/detail/12-11-2019-who-prequalifies-ebola-vaccine-paving-the-way-for-its-use-in-high-risk-countries|archive-date=November 15, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== In development ==\n{{Ebola virus disease epidemic}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Vaccine !! Associated organisations !! Status \n|-\n| Chimp adenovirus 3 vectored glycoprotein (cAd3-EBO Z) || [[GlaxoSmithKline|GSK]] & [[National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases|NIAID]] || Phase III Feb. 2016<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n|-\n| rVSV vectored glycoprotein (VSV-EBOV) || Newlink Genetics & [[Merck & Co.|Merck]] ||In use<ref>{{cite web|title=WHO coordinating vaccination of contacts to contain Ebola flare-up in Guinea|url=http://www.who.int/features/2016/ebola-contacts-vaccination/en/|publisher=[[World Health Organization]] (WHO)|access-date=20 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Vaccines alliance signs $5 million advance deal for Merck's Ebola shot|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-ebola-vaccine-idUSKCN0UY0OT|publisher=Reuters|access-date=20 July 2016|date=20 January 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Merck PR\" /><ref name=\"FDA PR\" />\n|-\n| Human adenovirus 5 vectored 2014 glycoprotein insert (Ad5-EBOV)  || BIT & CanSino || Phase I complete<ref name=\"pmid25817373\"/>\n|-\n| Adenovirus 26 vectored glycoprotein / MVA-BN (Ad26.ZEBOV/{{wbr}}MVA-BN) || [[Johnson & Johnson]]|| Phase I complete April, 2016<ref>{{ClinicalTrialsGov|NCT02313077|A Safety and Immunogenicity Study of Heterologous Prime-Boost Ebola Vaccine Regimens in Healthy Participants}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Milligan ID, Gibani MM, Sewell R, Clutterbuck EA, Campbell D, Plested E, Nuthall E, Voysey M, Silva-Reyes L, McElrath MJ, De Rosa SC, Frahm N, Cohen KW, Shukarev G, Orzabal N, van Duijnhoven W, Truyers C, Bachmayer N, Splinter D, Samy N, Pau MG, Schuitemaker H, Luhn K, Callendret B, Van Hoof J, Douoguih M, Ewer K, Angus B, Pollard AJ, Snape MD | display-authors = 6 | title = Safety and Immunogenicity of Novel Adenovirus Type 26- and Modified Vaccinia Ankara-Vectored Ebola Vaccines: A Randomized Clinical Trial | journal = JAMA | volume = 315 | issue = 15 | pages = 1610\u201323 | date = April 2016 | pmid = 27092831 | doi = 10.1001/jama.2016.4218 }}</ref>\n|-\n| HPIV-3 vectored glycoprotein || [[Ministry of Health (Russia)]]|| Phase I planned<ref>{{cite web |title = Ebola vaccines, therapies, and diagnostics |url = http://www.who.int/medicines/emp_ebola_q_as/en/ |date = 6 July 2015 |access-date = 10 September 2015 |publisher=[[World Health Organization]] (WHO)}}</ref>\n|-\n| Rabies vectored glycoprotein || [[Thomas Jefferson University]] & NIAID|| Non-human primate challenge complete<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Blaney JE, Marzi A, Willet M, Papaneri AB, Wirblich C, Feldmann F, Holbrook M, Jahrling P, Feldmann H, Schnell MJ | display-authors = 6 | title = Antibody quality and protection from lethal Ebola virus challenge in nonhuman primates immunized with rabies virus based bivalent vaccine | journal = PLOS Pathogens | volume = 9 | issue = 5 | pages = e1003389 | date = 30 May 2015 | pmid = 23737747 | pmc = 3667758 | doi = 10.1371/journal.ppat.1003389 }}</ref>\n|-\n| Purified glycoprotein || [[Protein Sciences]] || NHP challenge initiated<ref>{{cite web |title = CT lab hopes to stop spread of Ebola |url = http://www.wfsb.com/story/28016607/ct-lab-hopes-to-stop-spread-of-ebola |date = 3 March 2015 |access-date = 10 September 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| Ebola \u2206VP30 H2O2 treated || [[University of Wisconsin]]|| Non-human primate challenge complete<ref name=\"ReferenceB\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Marzi A, Halfmann P, Hill-Batorski L, Feldmann F, Shupert WL, Neumann G, Feldmann H, Kawaoka Y | display-authors = 6 | title = Vaccines. An Ebola whole-virus vaccine is protective in nonhuman primates | journal = Science | volume = 348 | issue = 6233 | pages = 439\u201342 | date = April 2015 | pmid = 25814063 | pmc = 4565490 | doi = 10.1126/science.aaa4919 }}</ref>\n|}\n\n=== cAd3-EBO Z ===\n[[File:Ebola virions.png|thumb|upright=.63636364|Ebola virions]]\n{{details|cAd3-ZEBOV}}\nIn September 2014, two Phase I clinical trials began for the vaccine [[cAd3-ZEBOV|cAd3-EBO Z]], which is based on an attenuated version of a chimpanzee [[adenovirus]] (cAd3) that has been genetically altered so that it is unable to replicate in humans.<ref name=VRCSept2014>{{cite web| title=Ebola Vaccine Clinical Development Overview (presentation)| url=http://www.who.int/immunization/diseases/ebola/2-GRAHAM_Ebo_WHO_Briefing_29Sept2014_final.pdf |author=[[Vaccine Research Center]], [[National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases|NIAID]]|date=2 October 2014| access-date=21 October 2014|publisher=[[World Health Organization]] (WHO)}}</ref> The cAd3 vector has a DNA fragment insert that encodes the Ebola virus glycoprotein, which is expressed on the virion surface and is critical for attachment to host cells and catalysis of membrane fusion.<ref name=prevail>{{ClinicalTrialsGov|NCT02344407|Partnership for Research on Ebola Vaccines in Liberia (PREVAIL)}}</ref> It was developed by [[National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases|NIAID]] in collaboration with Okairos, now a division of [[GlaxoSmithKline]]. For the trial designated VRC 20, 20 volunteers were recruited by the NIAID in Bethesda, Maryland, while three dose-specific groups of 20 volunteers each were recruited for trial EBL01 by University of Oxford, UK. Initial results were released in November 2014; all 20 volunteers developed antibodies against Ebola and there were no significant concerns raised about safety.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Ledgerwood JE, DeZure AD, Stanley DA, Coates EE, Novik L, Enama ME, Berkowitz NM, Hu Z, Joshi G, Ploquin A, Sitar S, Gordon IJ, Plummer SA, Holman LA, Hendel CS, Yamshchikov G, Roman F, Nicosia A, Colloca S, Cortese R, Bailer RT, Schwartz RM, Roederer M, Mascola JR, Koup RA, Sullivan NJ, Graham BS | display-authors = 6 | title = Chimpanzee Adenovirus Vector Ebola Vaccine | journal = The New England Journal of Medicine | volume = 376 | issue = 10 | pages = 928\u201338 | date = March 2017 | pmid = 25426834 | doi = 10.1056/NEJMoa1410863 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Stanley DA, Honko AN, Asiedu C, Trefry JC, Lau-Kilby AW, Johnson JC, Hensley L, Ammendola V, Abbate A, Grazioli F, Foulds KE, Cheng C, Wang L, Donaldson MM, Colloca S, Folgori A, Roederer M, Nabel GJ, Mascola J, Nicosia A, Cortese R, Koup RA, Sullivan NJ | display-authors = 6 | title = Chimpanzee adenovirus vaccine generates acute and durable protective immunity against ebolavirus challenge | journal = Nature Medicine | volume = 20 | issue = 10 | pages = 1126\u201329 | date = October 2014 | pmid = 25194571 | doi = 10.1038/nm.3702 }}</ref> In December 2014, University of Oxford expanded the trial to include a booster vaccine based on MVA-BN, a strain of [[Modified vaccinia Ankara]], developed by [[Bavarian Nordic]], to investigate whether it can help increase immune responses further.<ref>{{ClinicalTrialsGov|NCT02240875|A Study to Assess New Ebola Vaccines, cAd3-EBO Z and MVA-BN Filo}}</ref><ref name=UOONov2014>{{cite web| title=Booster Ebola vaccine enters first trials at Oxford University| url=http://www.ox.ac.uk/news/2014-12-04-booster-ebola-vaccine-enters-first-trials-oxford-university-0|author=University of Oxford|date=4 December 2014| access-date=7 December 2014| author-link=University of Oxford}}</ref>  The trial which has enrolled a total of 60 volunteers will see 30 volunteers vaccinated with the booster vaccine. {{As of|April 2015}}, Phase III trial with a single dose of cAd3-EBO Z begins in Sierra Leone after a successful Phase 2 study in West Africa countries.<ref name=NIHPR>{{cite press release|url= http://nih.gov/news/health/mar2015/niaid-26a.htm|title=Ebola test vaccines appear safe in Phase 2 Liberian clinical trial|publisher=[[National Institutes of Health]] (NIH)|date=26 March 2015}}</ref><ref name=CDCPR>{{cite press release|url=https://www.cdc.gov/media/releases/2015/p0414-ebola-vaccine.html|title=Ebola vaccine trial begins in Sierra Leone|date=14 April 2015|publisher=[[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] (CDC)}}</ref>\n\n=== Ad26.ZEBOV/MVA-BN ===\n[[Johnson & Johnson]] developed an Ebola vaccine at its [[Janssen Pharmaceutica]] Company. The regimen consists of two vaccine components (first vaccine as prime, followed by a second vaccine as [[booster dose|boost]])<ref name=BN>{{cite press release|url=http://www.bavarian-nordic.com/investor/news/news.aspx?news=4491|title=Bavarian Nordic announces that the Oxford Vaccines Group has initiated a Phase 2 study of the Ebola prime-boost vaccine regimen combining MVA-BN Filo and Janssen's Advac technology|author=Bavarian Nordic |location=Copenhagen, Denmark|publisher=Bavarian Nordic|date=15 July 2015|access-date=16 July 2015}}</ref> that are based on AdVac technology from [[Crucell]] Holland B.V., which is part of Janssen, and the MVA-BN technology from [[Bavarian Nordic]]. The Ad26.ZEBOV is derived from human adenovirus serotype 26 (Ad26) expressing the Ebola virus Mayinga variant glycoprotein while the second component MVA-BN is the [[Modified vaccinia Ankara|Modified Vaccinia Virus Ankara]] \u2013 Bavarian Nordic (MVA-BN) Filo-vector.<ref name=crucell>{{ClinicalTrialsGov|NCT02313077|A Safety and Immunogenicity Study of Heterologous Prime-Boost Ebola Vaccine Regimens in Healthy Participants}}</ref>  This product commenced Phase I [[clinical trial]] at the [[Edward Jenner Institute for Vaccine Research|Jenner Institute]] in Oxford during January 2015.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Walsh|first1=Fergus| name-list-format = vanc |title=Ebola: New vaccine trial begins|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/health-30696018|access-date=6 January 2015|publisher=[[BBC News Online]]|date=6 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release|title=Johnson & Johnson Announces Major Commitment to Speed Ebola Vaccine Development and Significantly Expand Production|url=http://www.jnj.com/news/all/Johnson-Johnson-Announces-Major-Commitment-to-Speed-Ebola-Vaccine-Development-and-Significantly-Expand-Production|publisher=Johnson & Johnson|access-date=6 January 2015}}</ref> The preliminary data indicated the prime-boost vaccine regimen elicited temporary immunologic response in the volunteers as expected from vaccination.  The Phase II trial enrolled 612 adult volunteers and commenced in July 2015, in the United Kingdom and France.  A second Phase II trial, involving 1,200 volunteers, was initiated in Africa<ref name=\"BN\"/> with the first trial commenced in Sierra Leone in October 2015.<ref name=jjsl>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2015/10/09/us-ebola-johnson-johnson-idUSKCN0S30EJ20151009|title=J&J starts vaccine trial in Sierra Leone, even as Ebola fades|last=Hirschler |first=Ben| name-list-format = vanc |publisher=Reuters|date=9 October 2015|access-date=15 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2019, the [[Committee for Medicinal Products for Human Use]] (CHMP) of the [[European Medicines Agency]] (EMA) granted an accelerated assessment to Janssen for Ad26.ZEBOV and MVA-BN,<ref name=\"JNJ PR\" /> and in November 2019, Janssen submitted a [[Marketing Authorization Application]] (MAA) to the EMA for approval of Ad26.ZEBOV and MVA-BN.<ref name=\"JNJ PR\">{{cite web | title=Johnson & Johnson Announces Submission of European Marketing Authorisation Applications for Janssen's Investigational Ebola Vaccine Regimen | website=Janssen | date=17 November 2019 | url=https://www.janssen.com/johnson-johnson-announces-submission-european-marketing-authorisation-applications-janssens | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191117013206/https://www.janssen.com/johnson-johnson-announces-submission-european-marketing-authorisation-applications-janssens | archive-date=17 November 2019 | url-status=live | access-date=16 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title=EU Marketing Authorisation submitted for Ebola vaccine regimen | first=Rachael | last=Harper | name-list-format = vanc | website=European Pharmaceutical Review | date=12 November 2019 | url=https://www.europeanpharmaceuticalreview.com/news/105108/eu-marketing-authorisation-ebola-vaccine-regimen/ | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191117013126/https://www.europeanpharmaceuticalreview.com/news/105108/eu-marketing-authorisation-ebola-vaccine-regimen/ | archive-date=17 November 2019 | url-status=live | access-date=16 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Ebola GP vaccine ===\n[[File:Recombinant formation of plasmids.svg|thumb|Recombinant formation plasmids]]\nAt the 8th Vaccine and ISV Conference in Philadelphia on 27\u221228 October 2014, [[Novavax]] Inc. reported the development in a \"few weeks\" of a [[glycoprotein]] (GP) [[nanoparticle]] Ebola virus (EBOV GP) vaccine using their proprietary [[recombinant DNA|recombinant]] technology. A recombinant protein is a protein whose code is carried by [[recombinant DNA]]. The vaccine is based on the newly published genetic sequence<ref name=\"Gire2014\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Gire SK, Goba A, Andersen KG, Sealfon RS, Park DJ, Kanneh L, Jalloh S, Momoh M, Fullah M, Dudas G, Wohl S, Moses LM, Yozwiak NL, Winnicki S, Matranga CB, Malboeuf CM, Qu J, Gladden AD, Schaffner SF, Yang X, Jiang PP, Nekoui M, Colubri A, Coomber MR, Fonnie M, Moigboi A, Gbakie M, Kamara FK, Tucker V, Konuwa E, Saffa S, Sellu J, Jalloh AA, Kovoma A, Koninga J, Mustapha I, Kargbo K, Foday M, Yillah M, Kanneh F, Robert W, Massally JL, Chapman SB, Bochicchio J, Murphy C, Nusbaum C, Young S, Birren BW, Grant DS, Scheiffelin JS, Lander ES, Happi C, Gevao SM, Gnirke A, Rambaut A, Garry RF, Khan SH, Sabeti PC | display-authors = 6 | title = Genomic surveillance elucidates Ebola virus origin and transmission during the 2014 outbreak | journal = Science | volume = 345 | issue = 6202 | pages = 1369\u201372 | date = September 2014 | pmid = 25214632 | pmc = 4431643 | doi = 10.1126/science.1259657 | bibcode = 2014Sci...345.1369G }}</ref> of the 2014 [[Ebola virus epidemic in Guinea|Guinea Ebola]] (Makona) strain that is responsible for the 2014 Ebola disease epidemic in West Africa.  In animal studies, a useful immune response was induced, and was found to be enhanced ten to a hundred-fold by the company's \"Matrix-M\" [[immunologic adjuvant]].  A study of the response of non-human primate to the vaccine had been initiated.  {{As of|February 2015}}, Novavax had completed two primate studies on baboons and macaques and had initiated a Phase I clinical trial in Australia. The Lipid nanoparticle (LNP)-encapsulated [[siRNA]]<nowiki/>s rapidly adapted to target the Makona outbreak strain of EBOV and are able to protect 100% of [[Rhesus macaque|rhesus monkey]]<nowiki/>s against lethal challenge when treatment was initiated at three days postexposure while animals were viremic and clinically ill.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Thi EP, Mire CE, Lee AC, Geisbert JB, Zhou JZ, Agans KN, Snead NM, Deer DJ, Barnard TR, Fenton KA, MacLachlan I, Geisbert TW | display-authors = 6 | title = Lipid nanoparticle siRNA treatment of Ebola-virus-Makona-infected nonhuman primates | journal = Nature | volume = 521 | issue = 7552 | pages = 362\u201365 | date = May 2015 | pmid = 25901685 | pmc = 4467030 | doi = 10.1038/nature14442 | bibcode = 2015Natur.521..362T }}</ref>\nThe top line Phase I human trial results showed that the adjuvanted Ebola GP Vaccine was highly immunogenic at all dose levels.{{medical citation needed|date=March 2016}}\n\n=== Nasal vaccine ===\nOn 5 November 2014, the ''[[Houston Chronicle]]'' reported that a research team at the [[University of Texas-Austin]] was developing a nasal spray Ebola vaccine, which the team had been working on for seven years.<ref name=HoustonChron/> The team reported in 2014, that in the nonhuman primate studies it conducted, the vaccine had more efficacy when delivered via nasal spray than by injection.<ref name=nasal>{{cite journal | vauthors = Choi JH, Jonsson-Schmunk K, Qiu X, Shedlock DJ, Strong J, Xu JX, Michie KL, Audet J, Fernando L, Myers MJ, Weiner D, Bajrovic I, Tran LQ, Wong G, Bello A, Kobinger GP, Schafer SC, Croyle MA | display-authors = 6 | title = A Single Dose Respiratory Recombinant Adenovirus-Based Vaccine Provides Long-Term Protection for Non-Human Primates from Lethal Ebola Infection | journal = Molecular Pharmaceutics | volume = 12 | issue = 8 | pages = 2712\u201331 | date = August 2015 | pmid = 25363619 | pmc = 4525323 | doi = 10.1021/mp500646d }}</ref> {{As of|November 2014}}, further development by the team appeared unlikely due to lack of funding.<ref name=HoustonChron>{{Cite news|url = http://www.houstonchronicle.com/local/prognosis/article/UT-nasal-spray-vaccine-for-Ebola-effective-in-5870548.php|title = UT nasal spray vaccine for Ebola effective in monkeys|last = Ackerman|first = Todd| name-list-format = vanc |date = 5 November 2014|work = [[Houston Chronicle]]|access-date = 13 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url = http://www.in-pharmatechnologist.com/Drug-Delivery/Ebola-nasal-vaccine-under-threat-as-funding-runs-dry|title = Ebola nasal vaccine under threat as funding runs dry|last = Stanton|first = Dan | name-list-format = vanc |date = 12 November 2014|work = in-PharmaTechnologist|access-date = 13 November 2014|publisher = William Reed Business Media|location = Crawley, Sussex, UK}}</ref>\n\n=== Vaxart tablet ===\nVaxart Inc. is developing a vaccine technology in the form of a temperature-stable tablet which may offer advantages such as reduced [[cold chain]] requirement, and rapid and scalable manufacturing. In January 2015, Vaxart announced that it had secured funding to develop its Ebola vaccine to Phase I trial.<ref>{{cite web|title=Vaxart Completes Financing to Fund Expanding Development Portfolio|url=http://www.pharmiweb.com/pressreleases/pressrel.asp?ROW_ID=106188#.VL1-P0ca9OI|publisher=Vaxart|access-date=19 January 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150119233716/http://www.pharmiweb.com/pressreleases/pressrel.asp?ROW_ID=106188#.VL1-P0ca9OI|archive-date=19 January 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n=== Novel recombinant adenovirus type-5 vector-based Ebola vaccine ===\nIn late 2014 and early 2015,  a double-blind, randomized Phase I trial was conducted in the [[Jiangsu Province]] of China; the trial examined a vaccine that contains [[glycoprotein]]s of the 2014 strain, rather than those of the 1976 strain. The trial found signals of efficacy and raised no significant safety concerns.<ref name=\"pmid25817373\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Zhu FC, Hou LH, Li JX, Wu SP, Liu P, Zhang GR, Hu YM, Meng FY, Xu JJ, Tang R, Zhang JL, Wang WJ, Duan L, Chu K, Liang Q, Hu JL, Luo L, Zhu T, Wang JZ, Chen W | display-authors = 6 | title = Safety and immunogenicity of a novel recombinant adenovirus type-5 vector-based Ebola vaccine in healthy adults in China: preliminary report of a randomised, double-blind, placebo-controlled, phase 1 trial | journal = Lancet | volume = 385 | issue = 9984 | pages = 2272\u201379 | date = June 2015 | pmid = 25817373 | doi = 10.1016/S0140-6736(15)60553-0 }}</ref>\n\n=== Attenuated Ebola Virus vaccine ===\nA study published in ''[[Science (journal)|Science]]'' during March 2015, demonstrated that vaccination with a weakened form of the Ebola virus provides some measure of protection to non-human primates. This study was conducted in accordance with a protocol approved by an Institutional Animal Care and Use Committee of the National Institutes of Health.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Marzi A, Feldmann F, Geisbert TW, Feldmann H, Safronetz D | title = Vesicular stomatitis virus-based vaccines against Lassa and Ebola viruses | journal = Emerging Infectious Diseases | volume = 21 | issue = 2 | pages = 305\u201307 | date = February 2015 | pmid = 25625358 | pmc = 4313664 | doi = 10.3201/eid2102.141649 }}</ref> The new vaccine relies on a strain of Ebola called EBOV\u0394VP30, which is unable to replicate.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\"/>\n\n=== GamEvac-Combi ===\nA study published in ''[[Human Vaccines & Immunotherapeutics]]'' in March 2017, analyzing data from a clinical trial of the GamEvac-Combi vaccine in Russia, concluded said vaccine to be safe and effective and recommended proceeding to Phase III trials.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Dolzhikova IV, Zubkova OV, Tukhvatulin AI, Dzharullaeva AS, Tukhvatulina NM, Shcheblyakov DV, Shmarov MM, Tokarskaya EA, Simakova YV, Egorova DA, Scherbinin DN, Tutykhina IL, Lysenko AA, Kostarnoy AV, Gancheva PG, Ozharovskaya TA, Belugin BV, Kolobukhina LV, Pantyukhov VB, Syromyatnikova SI, Shatokhina IV, Sizikova TV, Rumyantseva IG, Andrus AF, Boyarskaya NV, Voytyuk AN, Babira VF, Volchikhina SV, Kutaev DA, Bel'skih AN, Zhdanov KV, Zakharenko SM, Borisevich SV, Logunov DY, Naroditsky BS, Gintsburg AL | display-authors = 6 | title = Safety and immunogenicity of GamEvac-Combi, a heterologous VSV- and Ad5-vectored Ebola vaccine: An open phase I/II trial in healthy adults in Russia | journal = Human Vaccines & Immunotherapeutics | volume = 13 | issue = 3 | pages = 613\u201320 | date = March 2017 | pmid = 28152326 | pmc = 5360131 | doi = 10.1080/21645515.2016.1238535 }}</ref>\n\n=== Ad5-EBOV ===\nIn 2017, the [[National Medical Products Administration|China Food and Drug Administration]] (CFDA) announced approval of an Ebola vaccine, co-developed by the military-backed Bioengineering Institute of the Chinese Academy of Military Medical Sciences and private drugmaker Tianjin CanSino Biotechnology Inc.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.caixinglobal.com/2017-10-20/101159251.html |title=China Approves Ebola Vaccine |publisher=Caixin Global |first=Coco |last=Feng | name-list-format = vanc |date=2017-10-20 |access-date=2018-10-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181007111457/https://www.caixinglobal.com/2017-10-20/101159251.html |archive-date=2018-10-07 |url-status=dead }}</ref> It contains a [[human adenovirus]] serotype 5 vector (Ad5) with the glycoprotein gene from ZEBOV.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Wong G, Mendoza EJ, Plummer FA, Gao GF, Kobinger GP, Qiu X | title = From bench to almost bedside: the long road to a licensed Ebola virus vaccine | journal = Expert Opinion on Biological Therapy | volume = 18 | issue = 2 | pages = 159\u201373 | date = February 2018 | pmid = 29148858 | pmc = 5841470 | doi = 10.1080/14712598.2018.1404572 }}</ref> Their findings were consistent with previous tests on rVSV-ZEBOV in Africa and Europe.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.precisionvaccinations.com/ebola-vaccine-candidate-v920-approaching-finish-line|title=Ebola Vaccine Development Race Between the USA and China|first=Don Ward|last=Hackett | name-list-format = vanc |date=31 March 2018|website=Precision Vaccinations}}</ref>\n\n=== Prospects ===\nIn September 2019, a study published in ''[[Cell Reports]]'' demonstrated the role of the Ebola virus VP35 protein in its immune evasion. A recombinant form of Ebola virus with a mutant VP35 protein (VP35m) was developed, and showed positive results in the activation of the RIG-I-like receptor signaling. Non-human primates were challenged with different doses of VP35. This challenge resulted in the activation of the innate immune system and the production of anti-EBOV antibodies. The primates were then back-challenged with the wild type Ebola virus and survived. This potentially creates a prospect for a future vaccine development.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Woolsey C, Menicucci AR, Cross RW, Luthra P, Agans KN, Borisevich V, Geisbert JB, Mire CE, Fenton KA, Jankeel A, Anand S, Ebihara H, Geisbert TW, Messaoudi I, Basler CF | display-authors = 6 | title = A VP35 Mutant Ebola Virus Lacks Virulence but Can Elicit Protective Immunity to Wild-Type Virus Challenge | language = English | journal = Cell Reports | volume = 28 | issue = 12 | pages = 3032\u201346.e6 | date = September 2019 | pmid = 31533029 | pmc = 6886687 | doi = 10.1016/j.celrep.2019.08.047 | url = https://www.cell.com/cell-reports/abstract/S2211-1247(19)31095-2 }}</ref>\n\n== Clinical trials in West Africa ==\nIn January 2015,  Marie-Paule Kieny, the [[World Health Organization]]'s (WHO) assistant director-general of health systems and innovation, announced that the vaccines cAd3-EBO Z and VSV-EBOV had demonstrated acceptable safety profiles during early testing and would soon progress to large-scale trials in Liberia, Sierra Leone and Guinea. The trials would involve up to 27,000 people and comprise 3 groups \u2013 members of the first two groups would receive the two candidate vaccines, while the third group will receive a [[placebo]].<ref>{{cite web|title=UK leads promising Ebola vaccine trial Pharmaceutical company looking into largescale manufacturing if trials are successful|url=https://arstechnica.com/science/2015/01/uk-leads-promising-ebola-vaccine-trial/|work=[[Ars Technica]]|access-date=10 January 2015}}</ref>  Both vaccines have since successfully completed the [[Phases of clinical research|Phase 2]] studies.  The large scale [[Phases of clinical research|Phase 3]] studies have begun {{as of|April 2015|lc=yes}}, in Liberia and Sierra Leone,<ref name=\"NIHPR\"/><ref name=\"CDCPR\"/> and in Guinea in March 2016.<ref name=\"who.int\"/>\n\nIn addition, a medical anthropologist at [[Universit\u00e9 de Montr\u00e9al]], had been working in Guinea and raised further questions about safety in the ring trial after spending time in April at one of the Ebola treatment units where trial participants are taken if they become ill, the centre in Coyah, about 50{{nbsp}}km from the capital of Conakry.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Russia)|Russian Foreign Ministry]] announced in 2016, the intention to conduct field trials of two Russian vaccines involving 2000 people.<ref name=\"iol.co.za\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.iol.co.za/news/world/russia-to-fund-ebola-vaccine-trials-1998046|title=Russia to fund Ebola vaccine trials|access-date=2017-09-14}}</ref> According to local media reports, the Guinean government authorized the commencement of the trials on 9 August 2017, at the [[Rusal]]-built Research and Diagnostic Center of Epidemiology and Microbiology in [[Kindia Region|Kindia]]. The trials were slated to continue until 2018.<ref name=\"iol.co.za\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.afrique-sur7.fr/60736/guinee-vaccin-trouve-teste-contre-virus-ebola/|title=Guin\u00e9e: un vaccin trouv\u00e9 et test\u00e9 contre le virus Ebola \u2013 Afrique Sur 7 : actualit\u00e9 de notre Afrique et du monde|website=www.afrique-sur7.fr|language=fr|access-date=2017-09-14}}</ref> As of October 2019, Russia licensed the vaccine and was reportedly ready to ship vaccine to Africa.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tass.com/science/1084757|title=Russia ready to supply Ebola vaccine to Africa |date=|website=TASS|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-01}}</ref>\n\n==U.S. national stockpile==\nIn 2014, [[Credit Suisse]] estimated that the U.S. government will provide over $1{{nbsp}}billion in contracts to companies to develop medicine and vaccines for Ebola virus disease.<ref name = \"CNN 20141028\">{{Cite news | url = http://money.cnn.com/2014/10/28/news/companies/ebola-drug-billion/ | title = Ebola: The making of a $1 billion drug | last = Rooney | first = Ben | name-list-format = vanc | date = 28 October 2014 | work = [[CNN]] | access-date = 19 November 2014}}</ref> Congress passed a law in 2004, that funds a national stockpile of vaccines and medicine for possible outbreaks of disease.<ref name = \"CNN 20141028\" /> A number of companies were expected to develop Ebola vaccines: [[GlaxoSmithKline]], [[NewLink Genetics]], [[Johnson & Johnson]] and [[Bavarian Nordic]].<ref name = \"CNN 20141028\" /> Another company, [[Emergent BioSolutions]], was a contestant for manufacturing new doses of [[ZMapp]],{{cn|date=November 2019}} a drug for Ebola virus disease treatment originally developed by [[Mapp Biopharmaceutical]].<ref>{{Cite news | url = http://www.bizjournals.com/baltimore/news/2014/10/20/emergent-biosolutions-among-three-under.html | title = Emergent BioSolutions among three under consideration for Ebola drug manufacturing | last = Gantz | first = Sarah | name-list-format = vanc | date = 20 October 2014 | work = [[Baltimore Business Journal]] | access-date = 13 November 2014}}</ref> Supplies of ZMapp ran out in August 2014.<ref>{{cite news | title = Ebola test drug's supply 'exhausted' after shipments to Africa, U.S. company says | first1 = Lenny | last1 = Bernstein | first2 = Brady | last2 = Dennis | website = [[The Washington Post]] | name-list-format = vanc | date = 11 August 2014 | url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/health-science/ebola-test-drugs-supply-exhausted-after-shipments-to-africa-us-company-says/2014/08/11/020cefc0-2199-11e4-958c-268a320a60ce_story.html | access-date = 17 November 2019 }}</ref> In September 2014, the [[Biomedical Advanced Research and Development Authority]] (BARDA) entered into a multimillion-dollar contract with Mapp Biopharmaceutical to accelerate the development of ZMapp.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = McCarthy M | title = US signs contract with ZMapp maker to accelerate development of the Ebola drug | journal = BMJ | volume = 349 | issue = sep04 10 | pages = g5488 | date = September 2014 | pmid = 25189475 | doi = 10.1136/bmj.g5488 }}</ref> Additional contracts were signed in 2017.<ref>{{cite press release | title=MappBio Announces Contracts with BARDA for ZMapp and Additional Filovirus Medical Countermeasures | publisher=[[Mapp Biopharmaceutical]] | date=29 September 2017 | url=https://mappbio.com/mappbio-announces-contracts-barda-zmapptm-additional-filovirus-medical-countermeasures/ | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191117040246/https://mappbio.com/mappbio-announces-contracts-barda-zmapptm-additional-filovirus-medical-countermeasures/ | archive-date=17 November 2019 | url-status=live | access-date=16 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Ebola virus disease]]\n* [[Ebola virus disease treatment research]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|32em}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n{{refbegin|32em}}\n* {{cite journal | vauthors = Farooq F, Beck K, Paolino KM, Phillips R, Waters NC, Regules JA, Bergmann-Leitner ES | title = Circulating follicular T helper cells and cytokine profile in humans following vaccination with the rVSV-ZEBOV Ebola vaccine | journal = Scientific Reports | volume = 6 | pages = 27944 | date = June 2016 | pmid = 27323685 | pmc = 4914957 | doi = 10.1038/srep27944 | bibcode = 2016NatSR...627944F }}\n* {{cite journal | vauthors = Sullivan N, Yang ZY, Nabel GJ | title = Ebola virus pathogenesis: implications for vaccines and therapies | journal = Journal of Virology | volume = 77 | issue = 18 | pages = 9733\u20137 | date = September 2003 | pmid = 12941881 | pmc = 224575 | doi = 10.1128/JVI.77.18.9733-9737.2003 }}\n* {{cite journal | vauthors = Diakite I, Mooring EQ, Vel\u00e1squez GE, Murray MB | title = Novel Ordered Stepped-Wedge Cluster Trial Designs for Detecting Ebola Vaccine Efficacy Using a Spatially Structured Mathematical Model | journal = PLOS Neglected Tropical Diseases | volume = 10 | issue = 8 | pages = e0004866 | date = August 2016 | pmid = 27509037 | pmc = 4979980 | doi = 10.1371/journal.pntd.0004866 }}\n* {{cite journal | vauthors = Cazares LH, Ward MD, Brueggemann EE, Kenny T, Demond P, Mahone CR, Martins KA, Nuss JE, Glaros T, Bavari S | display-authors = 6 | title = Development of a liquid chromatography high resolution mass spectrometry method for the quantitation of viral envelope glycoprotein in Ebola virus-like particle vaccine preparations | journal = Clinical Proteomics | volume = 13 | issue = 1 | pages = 18 | date = 5 September 2016 | pmid = 27597813 | pmc = 5011338 | doi = 10.1186/s12014-016-9119-8 }}\n* {{cite journal | vauthors = Konduru K, Shurtleff AC, Bradfute SB, Nakamura S, Bavari S, Kaplan G | title = Ebolavirus Glycoprotein Fc Fusion Protein Protects Guinea Pigs against Lethal Challenge | journal = PloS One | volume = 11 | issue = 9 | pages = e0162446 | date = 13 September 2016 | pmid = 27622456 | pmc = 5021345 | doi = 10.1371/journal.pone.0162446 | bibcode = 2016PLoSO..1162446K }}\n* {{cite journal | vauthors = Cheng F, Murray JL, Zhao J, Sheng J, Zhao Z, Rubin DH | title = Systems Biology-Based Investigation of Cellular Antiviral Drug Targets Identified by Gene-Trap Insertional Mutagenesis | journal = PLOS Computational Biology | volume = 12 | issue = 9 | pages = e1005074 | date = September 2016 | pmid = 27632082 | pmc = 5025164 | doi = 10.1371/journal.pcbi.1005074 | bibcode = 2016PLSCB..12E5074C }}\n* {{cite journal | vauthors = Olowookere SA, Abioye-Kuteyi EA, Adekanle O | title = Willingness to participate in Ebola viral disease vaccine trials and receive vaccination by health workers in a tertiary hospital in Ile-Ife, Southwest Nigeria | journal = Vaccine | volume = 34 | issue = 47 | pages = 5758\u20135761 | date = November 2016 | pmid = 27751640 | doi = 10.1016/j.vaccine.2016.10.004 }}\n* {{cite journal | vauthors = Pavot V | title = Ebola virus vaccines: Where do we stand? | journal = Clinical Immunology | volume = 173 | pages = 44\u201349 | date = December 2016 | pmid = 27910805 | doi = 10.1016/j.clim.2016.10.016 }}\n* {{cite book|title=Completing the development of Ebola vaccines: current status, remaining challenges, and recommendations |vauthors=((The Wellcome Trust\u2013CIDRAP Ebola Vaccine Team B)) |date=January 2017|publisher=Center for Infectious Disease Research and Policy (CIDRAP) and Wellcome Trust|url=http://www.cidrap.umn.edu/completing-development-ebola-vaccines-team-b-report-3 |access-date=18 January 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170118225855/http://www.cidrap.umn.edu/sites/default/files/public/downloads/ebola_team_b_report_3-011717-final.pdf|archive-date=18 January 2017|url-status=live}}\n* {{cite journal | vauthors = Rosales-Mendoza S, Nieto-G\u00f3mez R, Angulo C | title = A Perspective on the Development of Plant-Made Vaccines in the Fight against Ebola Virus | journal = Frontiers in Immunology | volume = 8 | pages = 252 | date = 1 January 2017 | pmid = 28344580 | pmc = 5344899 | doi = 10.3389/fimmu.2017.00252 }}\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links==\n* {{MeshName|Ebola Vaccines}}\n{{Scholia|topic}}\n{{Filoviridae}}\n{{Vaccines}}\n{{Portal bar|Medicine|Viruses}}\n\n[[Category:Breakthrough therapy]]\n[[Category:Ebola]]\n[[Category:Hemorrhagic fevers]]\n[[Category:Vaccines]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Any of several vaccines to prevent Ebola}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox drug\n| drug_name         = \n| type              = vaccine\n| image             = Study Participant Receives NIAID-GSK Candidate Ebola Vaccine (3).jpg\n| caption           = Candidate ''Ebola vaccine'' being given\n| alt               = \n| width             = \n| image2            = \n| alt2              = \n| width2            = \n| target            = [[Zaire ebolavirus|Ebola virus]]\n| vaccine_type      = attenuated\n<!-- Clinical data -->\n| pronounce         = \n| tradename         = Ervebo\n| Drugs.com         = \n| MedlinePlus       = \n| licence_CA        = <!-- Health Canada may use generic or brand name (generic name preferred) -->\n| licence_EU        = <!-- EMA uses INN (or special INN_EMA) -->\n| DailyMedID        = <!-- DailyMed may use generic or brand name (generic name preferred) -->\n| licence_US        = Ervebo\n| pregnancy_AU      = <!-- A/B1/B2/B3/C/D/X -->\n| pregnancy_US      = <!-- A/B/C/D/X -->\n| pregnancy_category= \n| legal_AU = <!-- S2, S3, S4, S5, S6, S7, S8, S9 or Unscheduled -->\n| legal_BR =  <!-- OTC, A1, A2, A3, B1, B2, C1, C2, C3, C4, C5, D1, D2, E, F -->\n| legal_CA = <!-- OTC, Rx-only, Schedule I, II, III, IV, V, VI, VII, VIII -->\n| legal_UK = <!-- GSL, P, POM, CD, CD Lic, CD POM, CD No Reg POM, CD (Benz) POM, CD (Anab) POM or CD Inv POM -->\n| legal_US = Rx-only\n| legal_UN = <!-- N I, II, III, IV / P I, II, III, IV -->\n| legal_NZ = <!-- Class A, B, C -->\n| legal_status      = \n| dependency_liability = \n| addiction_liability = \n| routes_of_administration = \n<!-- Identifiers -->\n| CAS_number        = \n| CAS_supplemental  = \n| ATCvet            = \n| ATC_prefix        = J07\n| ATC_suffix        = BX02\n| ATC_supplemental  = \n| PubChem           = \n| PubChemSubstance  = \n| IUPHAR_ligand     = \n| DrugBank          = \n| ChemSpiderID      = \n| UNII              = \n| KEGG              = \n| ChEBI             = \n| ChEMBL            = \n| NIAID_ChemDB      = \n}}\n\n'''Ebola vaccines''' are a number of [[vaccines]] to prevent [[Ebola virus disease|Ebola]] that are either approved or in development. The first vaccine to be approved in the United States was [[rVSV-ZEBOV]] in December 2019.<ref name=\"FDA PR\">{{cite web | title=First FDA-approved vaccine for the prevention of Ebola virus disease, marking a critical milestone in public health preparedness and response | website=U.S. [[Food and Drug Administration]] (FDA) | date=19 December 2019 | url=https://www.fda.gov/news-events/press-announcements/first-fda-approved-vaccine-prevention-ebola-virus-disease-marking-critical-milestone-public-health | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191220052152/https://www.fda.gov/news-events/press-announcements/first-fda-approved-vaccine-prevention-ebola-virus-disease-marking-critical-milestone-public-health | archive-date=20 December 2019 | url-status=live | access-date=19 December 2019}} {{PD-notice}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.pharmatimes.com/news/us_approves_mercks_ebola_vaccine_1320832|title=US approves Merck's Ebola vaccine|last=McKee|first=Selina | name-list-format = vanc |date=23 December 2019|work=PharmaTimes Online|access-date=24 Dec 2019|url-status=live|publisher=PharmaTimes Media Limited|location=Surrey, England}}</ref>  It had been used extensively in [[DRC Ebola epidemic 2018-19|2018\u201319]] under  a [[compassionate use]] protocol.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://arstechnica.com/science/2019/04/ebola-vaccine-is-97-5-effective-early-outbreak-data-suggests/ |title = As Ebola outbreak rages, vaccine is 97.5% effective, protecting over 90K people|date = 2019-04-16}}</ref> Several promising vaccine candidates have been shown to protect nonhuman primates (usually [[macaques]]) against lethal infection.<ref name=\"Hoenen2012\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Hoenen T, Groseth A, Feldmann H | title = Current ebola vaccines | journal = Expert Opinion on Biological Therapy | volume = 12 | issue = 7 | pages = 859\u201372 | date = July 2012 | pmid = 22559078 | pmc = 3422127 | doi = 10.1517/14712598.2012.685152 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Peterson AT, Bauer JT, Mills JN | title = Ecologic and geographic distribution of filovirus disease | journal = Emerging Infectious Diseases | volume = 10 | issue = 1 | pages = 40\u201347 | date = January 2004 | pmid = 15078595 | pmc = 3322747 | doi = 10.3201/eid1001.030125 }}</ref><ref name=\"Hugues2012\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Fausther-Bovendo H, Mulangu S, Sullivan NJ | title = Ebolavirus vaccines for humans and apes | journal = Current Opinion in Virology | volume = 2 | issue = 3 | pages = 324\u201329 | date = June 2012 | pmid = 22560007 | pmc = 3397659 | doi = 10.1016/j.coviro.2012.04.003 }}</ref>\n\nVaccines include [[viral replication|replication]]-deficient [[adenovirus]] vectors, replication-competent [[vesicular stomatitis]] (VSV) and [[Human parainfluenza viruses|human parainfluenza]] (HPIV-3) vectors, and virus-like [[nanoparticle]] preparations. Conventional trials to study efficacy by exposure of humans to the pathogen after immunization are not ethical in this case. For such situations, the [[Food and Drug Administration]] (FDA) has established the \"[[Animal Efficacy Rule]]\" allowing licensure to be approved on the basis of [[animal model]] studies that replicate human disease, combined with evidence of safety and a potentially potent [[immune response]] (antibodies in the blood) from humans given the vaccine. [[Phases of clinical research|Clinical trials]] involve the administration of the vaccine to healthy human subjects to evaluate the immune response, identify any side effects and determine the appropriate dosage.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Pavot V | title = Ebola virus vaccines: Where do we stand? | journal = Clinical Immunology | volume = 173 | pages = 44\u201349 | date = December 2016 | pmid = 27910805 | doi = 10.1016/j.clim.2016.10.016 }}</ref>\n\n==Approved==\n=== rVSV-ZEBOV ===\n{{details|rVSV-ZEBOV}}\n\nVSV-EBOV or [[rVSV-ZEBOV]], sold under the brand name Ervebo, is a vaccine based on the [[vesicular stomatitis]] virus which was genetically modified to express a surface glycoprotein of Zaire Ebola virus.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Marzi A, Hanley PW, Haddock E, Martellaro C, Kobinger G, Feldmann H | title = Efficacy of Vesicular Stomatitis Virus-Ebola Virus Postexposure Treatment in Rhesus Macaques Infected With Ebola Virus Makona | journal = The Journal of Infectious Diseases | volume = 214 | issue = suppl 3 | pages = S360\u201366 | date = October 2016 | pmid = 27496978 | pmc = 5050468 | doi = 10.1093/infdis/jiw218 | url = https://academic.oup.com/jid/article-pdf/214/suppl_3/S360/7935990/jiw218.pdf }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Marzi A, Robertson SJ, Haddock E, Feldmann F, Hanley PW, Scott DP, Strong JE, Kobinger G, Best SM, Feldmann H | display-authors = 6 | title = Ebola Vaccine. VSV-EBOV rapidly protects macaques against infection with the 2014/15 Ebola virus outbreak strain | journal = Science | volume = 349 | issue = 6249 | pages = 739\u201342 | date = August 2015 | pmid = 26249231 | doi = 10.1126/science.aab3920 }}</ref> In November 2019, the European Commission granted a conditional marketing authorization.<ref>{{cite press release | title=Merck's Ervebo [Ebola Zaire Vaccine (rVSV\u0394G-ZEBOV-GP) live] Granted Conditional Approval in the European Union | publisher=Merck | via=Business Wire | date=11 November 2019 | url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20191111005601/en/Merck%E2%80%99s-ERVEBO%C2%AE-Ebola-Zaire-Vaccine-rVSV%CE%94G-ZEBOV-GP-live | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191111221058/https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20191111005601/en/Merck%E2%80%99s-ERVEBO%C2%AE-Ebola-Zaire-Vaccine-rVSV%CE%94G-ZEBOV-GP-live | archive-date=11 November 2019 | url-status=live | access-date=11 November 2019}}</ref> The WHO prequalification came fewer than 48 hours later, making it the fastest vaccine prequalification process ever conducted by WHO.<ref name=\":1\" /> In December 2019 it was approved for medical use in the United States.<ref name=\"FDA PR\" />\n\nIt was developed by the [[Public Health Agency of Canada]], with development subsequently taken over by [[Merck & Co.|Merck Inc]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/health/canadian-ebola-vaccine-development-taken-over-by-merck-1.2847128|title=Canadian Ebola vaccine development taken over by Merck|date=24 November 2014|publisher=[[CBC News]]|access-date=25 November 2014}}</ref> In October 2014, the [[Wellcome Trust]], who was also one of the biggest UK founders,<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Henao-Restrepo AM, Longini IM, Egger M, Dean NE, Edmunds WJ, Camacho A, Carroll MW, Doumbia M, Draguez B, Duraffour S, Enwere G, Grais R, Gunther S, Hossmann S, Kond\u00e9 MK, Kone S, Kuisma E, Levine MM, Mandal S, Norheim G, Riveros X, Soumah A, Trelle S, Vicari AS, Watson CH, K\u00e9\u00efta S, Kieny MP, R\u00f8ttingen JA | display-authors = 6 | title = Efficacy and effectiveness of an rVSV-vectored vaccine expressing Ebola surface glycoprotein: interim results from the Guinea ring vaccination cluster-randomised trial | journal = Lancet | volume = 386 | issue = 9996 | pages = 857\u201366 | date = August 2015 | pmid = 26248676 | doi = 10.1016/s0140-6736(15)61117-5 | hdl = 10144/575218 }}</ref> announced the start of multiple trials in healthy volunteers in Europe, Gabon, Kenya, and the US.<ref>{{cite press release |title=Multiple trials of VSV Ebola vaccine accelerated by international collaborative|url=http://www.wellcome.ac.uk/News/Media-office/Press-releases/2014/WTP057790.htm|publisher=Wellcome Trust|access-date=29 October 2014}}</ref> The vaccine was proven safe at multiple sites in North America, Europe, and Africa, but several volunteers at one trial site in Geneva, Switzerland, developed vaccine-related arthritis after about two weeks, and about 20\u201330% of volunteers at reporting sites developed low-grade post-vaccine fever, which resolved within a day or two. Other common side-effects were pain at the site of injection, myalgia, and fatigue.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Shuchman M | title = Ebola vaccine trial in west Africa faces criticism | journal = Lancet | volume = 385 | issue = 9981 | pages = 1933\u201334 | date = May 2015 | pmid = 25979835 | doi = 10.1016/s0140-6736(15)60938-2 }}</ref> The trial was temporarily halted in December 2014 due to possible adverse effects, but subsequently resumed.<ref>{{cite web |first1= Margaret |last1=Chan | name-list-format = vanc |authorlink1=Margaret Chan |title=WHO Director-General opens high-level meeting on Ebola vaccines|url=http://www.who.int/dg/speeches/2015/ebola-vaccines-meeting/en/|publisher=[[World Health Organization]] (WHO)|access-date=10 January 2015}}</ref> {{As of|April 2015}}, a Phase III trial with a single dose of VSV-EBOV began in Liberia after a successful Phase II study in the West African country.<ref name=\"NIHPR\"/> On 31 July 2015, preliminary results of a Phase III trial in Guinea indicated that the vaccine appears to be \"highly efficacious and safe.\"<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Henao-Restrepo AM, Longini IM, Egger M, Dean NE, Edmunds WJ, Camacho A, Carroll MW, Doumbia M, Draguez B, Duraffour S, Enwere G, Grais R, Gunther S, Hossmann S, Kond\u00e9 MK, Kone S, Kuisma E, Levine MM, Mandal S, Norheim G, Riveros X, Soumah A, Trelle S, Vicari AS, Watson CH, K\u00e9\u00efta S, Kieny MP, R\u00f8ttingen JA | display-authors = 6 | title = Efficacy and effectiveness of an rVSV-vectored vaccine expressing Ebola surface glycoprotein: interim results from the Guinea ring vaccination cluster-randomised trial | journal = Lancet | volume = 386 | issue = 9996 | pages = 857\u201366 | date = August 2015 | pmid = 26248676 | doi = 10.1016/S0140-6736(15)61117-5 | hdl = 10144/575218 }}</ref> The trial used a [[ring vaccination]] protocol that first vaccinated all the closest contacts of new cases of Ebola infection either immediately or after 21 days. Because of the demonstrated efficacy of immediate vaccination, all recipients will now be immunized immediately.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ebola update (93): Positive vaccine trial results |url=http://www.promedmail.org/direct.php?id=3552116|website=ProMED mail|publisher=International Society for Infectious Diseases|access-date=2 August 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"who.int\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.who.int/features/2016/ebola-contacts-vaccination/en/|title=WHO coordinating vaccination of contacts to contain Ebola flare-up in Guinea|date=March 2016|publisher=[[World Health Organization]] (WHO)|access-date=2016-05-14}}</ref> Ring vaccination is the method used in the program to eradicate [[smallpox]] in the 1970s. The trial will continue to assess whether the vaccine is effective in creating [[herd immunity]] to Ebola virus infection.<ref>{{cite press release|title=World on the verge of an effective Ebola vaccine|url=http://who.int/mediacentre/news/releases/2015/effective-ebola-vaccine/en/|publisher=[[World Health Organization]] (WHO)|date=31 July 2015}}</ref> In December 2016, a study found the VSV-EBOV vaccine to be 95\u2013100% effective against the Ebola virus, making it the first proven vaccine against the disease.<ref name=\"TL-20161222\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Henao-Restrepo AM, Camacho A, Longini IM, Watson CH, Edmunds WJ, Egger M, Carroll MW, Dean NE, Diatta I, Doumbia M, Draguez B, Duraffour S, Enwere G, Grais R, Gunther S, Gsell PS, Hossmann S, Watle SV, Kond\u00e9 MK, K\u00e9\u00efta S, Kone S, Kuisma E, Levine MM, Mandal S, Mauget T, Norheim G, Riveros X, Soumah A, Trelle S, Vicari AS, R\u00f8ttingen JA, Kieny MP | display-authors = 6 | title = Efficacy and effectiveness of an rVSV-vectored vaccine in preventing Ebola virus disease: final results from the Guinea ring vaccination, open-label, cluster-randomised trial (Ebola \u00c7a Suffit!) | journal = Lancet | volume = 389 | issue = 10068 | pages = 505\u201318 | date = February 2017 | pmid = 28017403 | pmc = 5364328 | doi = 10.1016/S0140-6736(16)32621-6 }}</ref><ref name=\"CNN-2016122\">{{cite news |last=Berlinger |first=Joshua | name-list-format = vanc |title=Ebola vaccine gives 100% protection, study finds |url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/12/22/health/ebola-vaccine-study/index.html |date=22 December 2016 |publisher=[[CNN]] |access-date=27 December 2016 }}</ref><ref name=\"WHO 23-12-2016\">{{cite press release | title=Final trial results confirm Ebola vaccine provides high protection against disease | website=[[World Health Organization]] (WHO) | date=23 December 2016 | url=https://www.who.int/en/news-room/detail/23-12-2016-final-trial-results-confirm-ebola-vaccine-provides-high-protection-against-disease | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191111230728/https://www.who.int/en/news-room/detail/23-12-2016-final-trial-results-confirm-ebola-vaccine-provides-high-protection-against-disease | archive-date=11 November 2019 | url-status=live | access-date=11 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe approval was supported by a study conducted in Guinea during the 2014\u20132016 outbreak in individuals 18 years of age and older.<ref name=\"FDA PR\" /> The study was a randomized cluster (ring) vaccination study in which 3,537 contacts, and contacts of contacts, of individuals with laboratory-confirmed Ebola virus disease (EVD) received either \"immediate\" or 21-day \"delayed\" vaccination.<ref name=\"FDA PR\" /> This noteworthy design was intended to capture a social network of individuals and locations that might include dwellings or workplaces where a patient spent time while symptomatic, or the households of individuals who had contact with the patient during that person's illness or death.<ref name=\"FDA PR\" /> In a comparison of cases of EVD among 2,108 individuals in the \"immediate\" vaccination arm and 1,429 individuals in the \"delayed\" vaccination arm, Ervebo was determined to be 100% effective in preventing Ebola cases with symptom onset greater than ten days after vaccination.<ref name=\"FDA PR\" /> No cases of EVD with symptom onset greater than ten days after vaccination were observed in the \"immediate\" cluster group, compared with ten cases of EVD in the 21-day \"delayed\" cluster group.<ref name=\"FDA PR\" />\n\nIn additional studies, antibody responses were assessed in 477 individuals in Liberia, approximately 500 individuals in Sierra Leone and approximately 900 individuals in Canada, Spain and the U.S.<ref name=\"FDA PR\" /> The antibody responses among those in the study conducted in Canada, Spain and the U.S. were similar to those among individuals in the studies conducted in Liberia and Sierra Leone.<ref name=\"FDA PR\" /> \n\nThe safety was assessed in approximately 15,000 individuals in Africa, Europe and North America.<ref name=\"FDA PR\" /> The most commonly reported side effects were pain, swelling and redness at the injection site, as well as headache, fever, joint and muscle aches and fatigue.<ref name=\"FDA PR\" />\n\nIn December 2016, a study found the [[VSV-EBOV]] vaccine to be 70\u2013100% effective against the Ebola virus, making it the first proven vaccine against the disease.<ref name=\"TL-20161222\" /><ref name=\"CNN-2016122\" /><ref name=\"WHO 23-12-2016\" /> However, the design of this study and the high efficacy of the vaccine were questioned.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Metzger WG, Vivas-Mart\u00ednez S | title = Questionable efficacy of the rVSV-ZEBOV Ebola vaccine | journal = Lancet | volume = 391 | issue = 10125 | pages = 1021 | date = March 2018 | pmid = 29565013 | doi = 10.1016/S0140-6736(18)30560-9 }}</ref> In November 2019, the European Commission granted a conditional marketing authorization to Ervebo (Ebola Zaire Vaccine (rVSV\u2206G-ZEBOV-GP, live))<ref name=\"Merck PR\">{{cite press release | title=Merck's Ervebo [Ebola Zaire Vaccine (rVSV\u0394G-ZEBOV-GP) live] Granted Conditional Approval in the European Union | publisher=Merck | via=Business Wire | date=November 11, 2019 | url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20191111005601/en/Merck%E2%80%99s-ERVEBO%C2%AE-Ebola-Zaire-Vaccine-rVSV%CE%94G-ZEBOV-GP-live | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191111221058/https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20191111005601/en/Merck%E2%80%99s-ERVEBO%C2%AE-Ebola-Zaire-Vaccine-rVSV%CE%94G-ZEBOV-GP-live | archive-date=November 11, 2019 | url-status=live | access-date=November 11, 2019}}</ref> and the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) prequalified an Ebola vaccine for the first time.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite press release|url=https://www.who.int/news-room/detail/12-11-2019-who-prequalifies-ebola-vaccine-paving-the-way-for-its-use-in-high-risk-countries|title=WHO prequalifies Ebola vaccine, paving the way for its use in high-risk countries|website=[[World Health Organization]] (WHO)|date=November 12, 2019|access-date=2019-11-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191115045218/https://www.who.int/news-room/detail/12-11-2019-who-prequalifies-ebola-vaccine-paving-the-way-for-its-use-in-high-risk-countries|archive-date=November 15, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== In development ==\n{{Ebola virus disease epidemic}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Vaccine !! Associated organisations !! Status \n|-\n| Chimp adenovirus 3 vectored glycoprotein (cAd3-EBO Z) || [[GlaxoSmithKline|GSK]] & [[National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases|NIAID]] || Phase III Feb. 2016<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n|-\n| rVSV vectored glycoprotein (VSV-EBOV) || Newlink Genetics & [[Merck & Co.|Merck]] ||In use<ref>{{cite web|title=WHO coordinating vaccination of contacts to contain Ebola flare-up in Guinea|url=http://www.who.int/features/2016/ebola-contacts-vaccination/en/|publisher=[[World Health Organization]] (WHO)|access-date=20 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Vaccines alliance signs $5 million advance deal for Merck's Ebola shot|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-ebola-vaccine-idUSKCN0UY0OT|publisher=Reuters|access-date=20 July 2016|date=20 January 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Merck PR\" /><ref name=\"FDA PR\" />\n|-\n| Human adenovirus 5 vectored 2014 glycoprotein insert (Ad5-EBOV)  || BIT & CanSino || Phase I complete<ref name=\"pmid25817373\"/>\n|-\n| Adenovirus 26 vectored glycoprotein / MVA-BN (Ad26.ZEBOV/{{wbr}}MVA-BN) || [[Johnson & Johnson]]|| Phase I complete April, 2016<ref>{{ClinicalTrialsGov|NCT02313077|A Safety and Immunogenicity Study of Heterologous Prime-Boost Ebola Vaccine Regimens in Healthy Participants}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Milligan ID, Gibani MM, Sewell R, Clutterbuck EA, Campbell D, Plested E, Nuthall E, Voysey M, Silva-Reyes L, McElrath MJ, De Rosa SC, Frahm N, Cohen KW, Shukarev G, Orzabal N, van Duijnhoven W, Truyers C, Bachmayer N, Splinter D, Samy N, Pau MG, Schuitemaker H, Luhn K, Callendret B, Van Hoof J, Douoguih M, Ewer K, Angus B, Pollard AJ, Snape MD | display-authors = 6 | title = Safety and Immunogenicity of Novel Adenovirus Type 26- and Modified Vaccinia Ankara-Vectored Ebola Vaccines: A Randomized Clinical Trial | journal = JAMA | volume = 315 | issue = 15 | pages = 1610\u201323 | date = April 2016 | pmid = 27092831 | doi = 10.1001/jama.2016.4218 }}</ref>\n|-\n| HPIV-3 vectored glycoprotein || [[Ministry of Health (Russia)]]|| Phase I planned<ref>{{cite web |title = Ebola vaccines, therapies, and diagnostics |url = http://www.who.int/medicines/emp_ebola_q_as/en/ |date = 6 July 2015 |access-date = 10 September 2015 |publisher=[[World Health Organization]] (WHO)}}</ref>\n|-\n| Rabies vectored glycoprotein || [[Thomas Jefferson University]] & NIAID|| Non-human primate challenge complete<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Blaney JE, Marzi A, Willet M, Papaneri AB, Wirblich C, Feldmann F, Holbrook M, Jahrling P, Feldmann H, Schnell MJ | display-authors = 6 | title = Antibody quality and protection from lethal Ebola virus challenge in nonhuman primates immunized with rabies virus based bivalent vaccine | journal = PLOS Pathogens | volume = 9 | issue = 5 | pages = e1003389 | date = 30 May 2015 | pmid = 23737747 | pmc = 3667758 | doi = 10.1371/journal.ppat.1003389 }}</ref>\n|-\n| Purified glycoprotein || [[Protein Sciences]] || NHP challenge initiated<ref>{{cite web |title = CT lab hopes to stop spread of Ebola |url = http://www.wfsb.com/story/28016607/ct-lab-hopes-to-stop-spread-of-ebola |date = 3 March 2015 |access-date = 10 September 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| Ebola \u2206VP30 H2O2 treated || [[University of Wisconsin]]|| Non-human primate challenge complete<ref name=\"ReferenceB\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Marzi A, Halfmann P, Hill-Batorski L, Feldmann F, Shupert WL, Neumann G, Feldmann H, Kawaoka Y | display-authors = 6 | title = Vaccines. An Ebola whole-virus vaccine is protective in nonhuman primates | journal = Science | volume = 348 | issue = 6233 | pages = 439\u201342 | date = April 2015 | pmid = 25814063 | pmc = 4565490 | doi = 10.1126/science.aaa4919 }}</ref>\n|}\n\n=== cAd3-EBO Z ===\n[[File:Ebola virions.png|thumb|upright=.63636364|Ebola virions]]\n{{details|cAd3-ZEBOV}}\nIn September 2014, two Phase I clinical trials began for the vaccine [[cAd3-ZEBOV|cAd3-EBO Z]], which is based on an attenuated version of a chimpanzee [[adenovirus]] (cAd3) that has been genetically altered so that it is unable to replicate in humans.<ref name=VRCSept2014>{{cite web| title=Ebola Vaccine Clinical Development Overview (presentation)| url=http://www.who.int/immunization/diseases/ebola/2-GRAHAM_Ebo_WHO_Briefing_29Sept2014_final.pdf |author=[[Vaccine Research Center]], [[National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases|NIAID]]|date=2 October 2014| access-date=21 October 2014|publisher=[[World Health Organization]] (WHO)}}</ref> The cAd3 vector has a DNA fragment insert that encodes the Ebola virus glycoprotein, which is expressed on the virion surface and is critical for attachment to host cells and catalysis of membrane fusion.<ref name=prevail>{{ClinicalTrialsGov|NCT02344407|Partnership for Research on Ebola Vaccines in Liberia (PREVAIL)}}</ref> It was developed by [[National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases|NIAID]] in collaboration with Okairos, now a division of [[GlaxoSmithKline]]. For the trial designated VRC 20, 20 volunteers were recruited by the NIAID in Bethesda, Maryland, while three dose-specific groups of 20 volunteers each were recruited for trial EBL01 by University of Oxford, UK. Initial results were released in November 2014; all 20 volunteers developed antibodies against Ebola and there were no significant concerns raised about safety.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Ledgerwood JE, DeZure AD, Stanley DA, Coates EE, Novik L, Enama ME, Berkowitz NM, Hu Z, Joshi G, Ploquin A, Sitar S, Gordon IJ, Plummer SA, Holman LA, Hendel CS, Yamshchikov G, Roman F, Nicosia A, Colloca S, Cortese R, Bailer RT, Schwartz RM, Roederer M, Mascola JR, Koup RA, Sullivan NJ, Graham BS | display-authors = 6 | title = Chimpanzee Adenovirus Vector Ebola Vaccine | journal = The New England Journal of Medicine | volume = 376 | issue = 10 | pages = 928\u201338 | date = March 2017 | pmid = 25426834 | doi = 10.1056/NEJMoa1410863 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Stanley DA, Honko AN, Asiedu C, Trefry JC, Lau-Kilby AW, Johnson JC, Hensley L, Ammendola V, Abbate A, Grazioli F, Foulds KE, Cheng C, Wang L, Donaldson MM, Colloca S, Folgori A, Roederer M, Nabel GJ, Mascola J, Nicosia A, Cortese R, Koup RA, Sullivan NJ | display-authors = 6 | title = Chimpanzee adenovirus vaccine generates acute and durable protective immunity against ebolavirus challenge | journal = Nature Medicine | volume = 20 | issue = 10 | pages = 1126\u201329 | date = October 2014 | pmid = 25194571 | doi = 10.1038/nm.3702 }}</ref> In December 2014, University of Oxford expanded the trial to include a booster vaccine based on MVA-BN, a strain of [[Modified vaccinia Ankara]], developed by [[Bavarian Nordic]], to investigate whether it can help increase immune responses further.<ref>{{ClinicalTrialsGov|NCT02240875|A Study to Assess New Ebola Vaccines, cAd3-EBO Z and MVA-BN Filo}}</ref><ref name=UOONov2014>{{cite web| title=Booster Ebola vaccine enters first trials at Oxford University| url=http://www.ox.ac.uk/news/2014-12-04-booster-ebola-vaccine-enters-first-trials-oxford-university-0|author=University of Oxford|date=4 December 2014| access-date=7 December 2014| author-link=University of Oxford}}</ref>  The trial which has enrolled a total of 60 volunteers will see 30 volunteers vaccinated with the booster vaccine. {{As of|April 2015}}, Phase III trial with a single dose of cAd3-EBO Z begins in Sierra Leone after a successful Phase 2 study in West Africa countries.<ref name=NIHPR>{{cite press release|url= http://nih.gov/news/health/mar2015/niaid-26a.htm|title=Ebola test vaccines appear safe in Phase 2 Liberian clinical trial|publisher=[[National Institutes of Health]] (NIH)|date=26 March 2015}}</ref><ref name=CDCPR>{{cite press release|url=https://www.cdc.gov/media/releases/2015/p0414-ebola-vaccine.html|title=Ebola vaccine trial begins in Sierra Leone|date=14 April 2015|publisher=[[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] (CDC)}}</ref>\n\n=== Ad26.ZEBOV/MVA-BN ===\n[[Johnson & Johnson]] developed an Ebola vaccine at its [[Janssen Pharmaceutica]] Company. The regimen consists of two vaccine components (first vaccine as prime, followed by a second vaccine as [[booster dose|boost]])<ref name=BN>{{cite press release|url=http://www.bavarian-nordic.com/investor/news/news.aspx?news=4491|title=Bavarian Nordic announces that the Oxford Vaccines Group has initiated a Phase 2 study of the Ebola prime-boost vaccine regimen combining MVA-BN Filo and Janssen's Advac technology|author=Bavarian Nordic |location=Copenhagen, Denmark|publisher=Bavarian Nordic|date=15 July 2015|access-date=16 July 2015}}</ref> that are based on AdVac technology from [[Crucell]] Holland B.V., which is part of Janssen, and the MVA-BN technology from [[Bavarian Nordic]]. The Ad26.ZEBOV is derived from human adenovirus serotype 26 (Ad26) expressing the Ebola virus Mayinga variant glycoprotein while the second component MVA-BN is the [[Modified vaccinia Ankara|Modified Vaccinia Virus Ankara]] \u2013 Bavarian Nordic (MVA-BN) Filo-vector.<ref name=crucell>{{ClinicalTrialsGov|NCT02313077|A Safety and Immunogenicity Study of Heterologous Prime-Boost Ebola Vaccine Regimens in Healthy Participants}}</ref>  This product commenced Phase I [[clinical trial]] at the [[Edward Jenner Institute for Vaccine Research|Jenner Institute]] in Oxford during January 2015.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Walsh|first1=Fergus| name-list-format = vanc |title=Ebola: New vaccine trial begins|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/health-30696018|access-date=6 January 2015|publisher=[[BBC News Online]]|date=6 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release|title=Johnson & Johnson Announces Major Commitment to Speed Ebola Vaccine Development and Significantly Expand Production|url=http://www.jnj.com/news/all/Johnson-Johnson-Announces-Major-Commitment-to-Speed-Ebola-Vaccine-Development-and-Significantly-Expand-Production|publisher=Johnson & Johnson|access-date=6 January 2015}}</ref> The preliminary data indicated the prime-boost vaccine regimen elicited temporary immunologic response in the volunteers as expected from vaccination.  The Phase II trial enrolled 612 adult volunteers and commenced in July 2015, in the United Kingdom and France.  A second Phase II trial, involving 1,200 volunteers, was initiated in Africa<ref name=\"BN\"/> with the first trial commenced in Sierra Leone in October 2015.<ref name=jjsl>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2015/10/09/us-ebola-johnson-johnson-idUSKCN0S30EJ20151009|title=J&J starts vaccine trial in Sierra Leone, even as Ebola fades|last=Hirschler |first=Ben| name-list-format = vanc |publisher=Reuters|date=9 October 2015|access-date=15 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2019, the [[Committee for Medicinal Products for Human Use]] (CHMP) of the [[European Medicines Agency]] (EMA) granted an accelerated assessment to Janssen for Ad26.ZEBOV and MVA-BN,<ref name=\"JNJ PR\" /> and in November 2019, Janssen submitted a [[Marketing Authorization Application]] (MAA) to the EMA for approval of Ad26.ZEBOV and MVA-BN.<ref name=\"JNJ PR\">{{cite web | title=Johnson & Johnson Announces Submission of European Marketing Authorisation Applications for Janssen's Investigational Ebola Vaccine Regimen | website=Janssen | date=17 November 2019 | url=https://www.janssen.com/johnson-johnson-announces-submission-european-marketing-authorisation-applications-janssens | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191117013206/https://www.janssen.com/johnson-johnson-announces-submission-european-marketing-authorisation-applications-janssens | archive-date=17 November 2019 | url-status=live | access-date=16 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title=EU Marketing Authorisation submitted for Ebola vaccine regimen | first=Rachael | last=Harper | name-list-format = vanc | website=European Pharmaceutical Review | date=12 November 2019 | url=https://www.europeanpharmaceuticalreview.com/news/105108/eu-marketing-authorisation-ebola-vaccine-regimen/ | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191117013126/https://www.europeanpharmaceuticalreview.com/news/105108/eu-marketing-authorisation-ebola-vaccine-regimen/ | archive-date=17 November 2019 | url-status=live | access-date=16 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Ebola GP vaccine ===\n[[File:Recombinant formation of plasmids.svg|thumb|Recombinant formation plasmids]]\nAt the 8th Vaccine and ISV Conference in Philadelphia on 27\u221228 October 2014, [[Novavax]] Inc. reported the development in a \"few weeks\" of a [[glycoprotein]] (GP) [[nanoparticle]] Ebola virus (EBOV GP) vaccine using their proprietary [[recombinant DNA|recombinant]] technology. A recombinant protein is a protein whose code is carried by [[recombinant DNA]]. The vaccine is based on the newly published genetic sequence<ref name=\"Gire2014\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Gire SK, Goba A, Andersen KG, Sealfon RS, Park DJ, Kanneh L, Jalloh S, Momoh M, Fullah M, Dudas G, Wohl S, Moses LM, Yozwiak NL, Winnicki S, Matranga CB, Malboeuf CM, Qu J, Gladden AD, Schaffner SF, Yang X, Jiang PP, Nekoui M, Colubri A, Coomber MR, Fonnie M, Moigboi A, Gbakie M, Kamara FK, Tucker V, Konuwa E, Saffa S, Sellu J, Jalloh AA, Kovoma A, Koninga J, Mustapha I, Kargbo K, Foday M, Yillah M, Kanneh F, Robert W, Massally JL, Chapman SB, Bochicchio J, Murphy C, Nusbaum C, Young S, Birren BW, Grant DS, Scheiffelin JS, Lander ES, Happi C, Gevao SM, Gnirke A, Rambaut A, Garry RF, Khan SH, Sabeti PC | display-authors = 6 | title = Genomic surveillance elucidates Ebola virus origin and transmission during the 2014 outbreak | journal = Science | volume = 345 | issue = 6202 | pages = 1369\u201372 | date = September 2014 | pmid = 25214632 | pmc = 4431643 | doi = 10.1126/science.1259657 | bibcode = 2014Sci...345.1369G }}</ref> of the 2014 [[Ebola virus epidemic in Guinea|Guinea Ebola]] (Makona) strain that is responsible for the 2014 Ebola disease epidemic in West Africa.  In animal studies, a useful immune response was induced, and was found to be enhanced ten to a hundred-fold by the company's \"Matrix-M\" [[immunologic adjuvant]].  A study of the response of non-human primate to the vaccine had been initiated.  {{As of|February 2015}}, Novavax had completed two primate studies on baboons and macaques and had initiated a Phase I clinical trial in Australia. The Lipid nanoparticle (LNP)-encapsulated [[siRNA]]<nowiki/>s rapidly adapted to target the Makona outbreak strain of EBOV and are able to protect 100% of [[Rhesus macaque|rhesus monkey]]<nowiki/>s against lethal challenge when treatment was initiated at three days postexposure while animals were viremic and clinically ill.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Thi EP, Mire CE, Lee AC, Geisbert JB, Zhou JZ, Agans KN, Snead NM, Deer DJ, Barnard TR, Fenton KA, MacLachlan I, Geisbert TW | display-authors = 6 | title = Lipid nanoparticle siRNA treatment of Ebola-virus-Makona-infected nonhuman primates | journal = Nature | volume = 521 | issue = 7552 | pages = 362\u201365 | date = May 2015 | pmid = 25901685 | pmc = 4467030 | doi = 10.1038/nature14442 | bibcode = 2015Natur.521..362T }}</ref>\nThe top line Phase I human trial results showed that the adjuvanted Ebola GP Vaccine was highly immunogenic at all dose levels.{{medical citation needed|date=March 2016}}\n\n=== Nasal vaccine ===\nOn 5 November 2014, the ''[[Houston Chronicle]]'' reported that a research team at the [[University of Texas-Austin]] was developing a nasal spray Ebola vaccine, which the team had been working on for seven years.<ref name=HoustonChron/> The team reported in 2014, that in the nonhuman primate studies it conducted, the vaccine had more efficacy when delivered via nasal spray than by injection.<ref name=nasal>{{cite journal | vauthors = Choi JH, Jonsson-Schmunk K, Qiu X, Shedlock DJ, Strong J, Xu JX, Michie KL, Audet J, Fernando L, Myers MJ, Weiner D, Bajrovic I, Tran LQ, Wong G, Bello A, Kobinger GP, Schafer SC, Croyle MA | display-authors = 6 | title = A Single Dose Respiratory Recombinant Adenovirus-Based Vaccine Provides Long-Term Protection for Non-Human Primates from Lethal Ebola Infection | journal = Molecular Pharmaceutics | volume = 12 | issue = 8 | pages = 2712\u201331 | date = August 2015 | pmid = 25363619 | pmc = 4525323 | doi = 10.1021/mp500646d }}</ref> {{As of|November 2014}}, further development by the team appeared unlikely due to lack of funding.<ref name=HoustonChron>{{Cite news|url = http://www.houstonchronicle.com/local/prognosis/article/UT-nasal-spray-vaccine-for-Ebola-effective-in-5870548.php|title = UT nasal spray vaccine for Ebola effective in monkeys|last = Ackerman|first = Todd| name-list-format = vanc |date = 5 November 2014|work = [[Houston Chronicle]]|access-date = 13 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url = http://www.in-pharmatechnologist.com/Drug-Delivery/Ebola-nasal-vaccine-under-threat-as-funding-runs-dry|title = Ebola nasal vaccine under threat as funding runs dry|last = Stanton|first = Dan | name-list-format = vanc |date = 12 November 2014|work = in-PharmaTechnologist|access-date = 13 November 2014|publisher = William Reed Business Media|location = Crawley, Sussex, UK}}</ref>\n\n=== Vaxart tablet ===\nVaxart Inc. is developing a vaccine technology in the form of a temperature-stable tablet which may offer advantages such as reduced [[cold chain]] requirement, and rapid and scalable manufacturing. In January 2015, Vaxart announced that it had secured funding to develop its Ebola vaccine to Phase I trial.<ref>{{cite web|title=Vaxart Completes Financing to Fund Expanding Development Portfolio|url=http://www.pharmiweb.com/pressreleases/pressrel.asp?ROW_ID=106188#.VL1-P0ca9OI|publisher=Vaxart|access-date=19 January 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150119233716/http://www.pharmiweb.com/pressreleases/pressrel.asp?ROW_ID=106188#.VL1-P0ca9OI|archive-date=19 January 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n=== Novel recombinant adenovirus type-5 vector-based Ebola vaccine ===\nIn late 2014 and early 2015,  a double-blind, randomized Phase I trial was conducted in the [[Jiangsu Province]] of China; the trial examined a vaccine that contains [[glycoprotein]]s of the 2014 strain, rather than those of the 1976 strain. The trial found signals of efficacy and raised no significant safety concerns.<ref name=\"pmid25817373\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Zhu FC, Hou LH, Li JX, Wu SP, Liu P, Zhang GR, Hu YM, Meng FY, Xu JJ, Tang R, Zhang JL, Wang WJ, Duan L, Chu K, Liang Q, Hu JL, Luo L, Zhu T, Wang JZ, Chen W | display-authors = 6 | title = Safety and immunogenicity of a novel recombinant adenovirus type-5 vector-based Ebola vaccine in healthy adults in China: preliminary report of a randomised, double-blind, placebo-controlled, phase 1 trial | journal = Lancet | volume = 385 | issue = 9984 | pages = 2272\u201379 | date = June 2015 | pmid = 25817373 | doi = 10.1016/S0140-6736(15)60553-0 }}</ref>\n\n=== Attenuated Ebola Virus vaccine ===\nA study published in ''[[Science (journal)|Science]]'' during March 2015, demonstrated that vaccination with a weakened form of the Ebola virus provides some measure of protection to non-human primates. This study was conducted in accordance with a protocol approved by an Institutional Animal Care and Use Committee of the National Institutes of Health.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Marzi A, Feldmann F, Geisbert TW, Feldmann H, Safronetz D | title = Vesicular stomatitis virus-based vaccines against Lassa and Ebola viruses | journal = Emerging Infectious Diseases | volume = 21 | issue = 2 | pages = 305\u201307 | date = February 2015 | pmid = 25625358 | pmc = 4313664 | doi = 10.3201/eid2102.141649 }}</ref> The new vaccine relies on a strain of Ebola called EBOV\u0394VP30, which is unable to replicate.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\"/>\n\n=== GamEvac-Combi ===\nA study published in ''[[Human Vaccines & Immunotherapeutics]]'' in March 2017, analyzing data from a clinical trial of the GamEvac-Combi vaccine in Russia, concluded said vaccine to be safe and effective and recommended proceeding to Phase III trials.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Dolzhikova IV, Zubkova OV, Tukhvatulin AI, Dzharullaeva AS, Tukhvatulina NM, Shcheblyakov DV, Shmarov MM, Tokarskaya EA, Simakova YV, Egorova DA, Scherbinin DN, Tutykhina IL, Lysenko AA, Kostarnoy AV, Gancheva PG, Ozharovskaya TA, Belugin BV, Kolobukhina LV, Pantyukhov VB, Syromyatnikova SI, Shatokhina IV, Sizikova TV, Rumyantseva IG, Andrus AF, Boyarskaya NV, Voytyuk AN, Babira VF, Volchikhina SV, Kutaev DA, Bel'skih AN, Zhdanov KV, Zakharenko SM, Borisevich SV, Logunov DY, Naroditsky BS, Gintsburg AL | display-authors = 6 | title = Safety and immunogenicity of GamEvac-Combi, a heterologous VSV- and Ad5-vectored Ebola vaccine: An open phase I/II trial in healthy adults in Russia | journal = Human Vaccines & Immunotherapeutics | volume = 13 | issue = 3 | pages = 613\u201320 | date = March 2017 | pmid = 28152326 | pmc = 5360131 | doi = 10.1080/21645515.2016.1238535 }}</ref>\n\n=== Ad5-EBOV ===\nIn 2017, the [[National Medical Products Administration|China Food and Drug Administration]] (CFDA) announced approval of an Ebola vaccine, co-developed by the military-backed Bioengineering Institute of the Chinese Academy of Military Medical Sciences and private drugmaker Tianjin CanSino Biotechnology Inc.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.caixinglobal.com/2017-10-20/101159251.html |title=China Approves Ebola Vaccine |publisher=Caixin Global |first=Coco |last=Feng | name-list-format = vanc |date=2017-10-20 |access-date=2018-10-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181007111457/https://www.caixinglobal.com/2017-10-20/101159251.html |archive-date=2018-10-07 |url-status=dead }}</ref> It contains a [[human adenovirus]] serotype 5 vector (Ad5) with the glycoprotein gene from ZEBOV.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Wong G, Mendoza EJ, Plummer FA, Gao GF, Kobinger GP, Qiu X | title = From bench to almost bedside: the long road to a licensed Ebola virus vaccine | journal = Expert Opinion on Biological Therapy | volume = 18 | issue = 2 | pages = 159\u201373 | date = February 2018 | pmid = 29148858 | pmc = 5841470 | doi = 10.1080/14712598.2018.1404572 }}</ref> Their findings were consistent with previous tests on rVSV-ZEBOV in Africa and Europe.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.precisionvaccinations.com/ebola-vaccine-candidate-v920-approaching-finish-line|title=Ebola Vaccine Development Race Between the USA and China|first=Don Ward|last=Hackett | name-list-format = vanc |date=31 March 2018|website=Precision Vaccinations}}</ref>\n\n=== Prospects ===\nIn September 2019, a study published in ''[[Cell Reports]]'' demonstrated the role of the Ebola virus VP35 protein in its immune evasion. A recombinant form of Ebola virus with a mutant VP35 protein (VP35m) was developed, and showed positive results in the activation of the RIG-I-like receptor signaling. Non-human primates were challenged with different doses of VP35. This challenge resulted in the activation of the innate immune system and the production of anti-EBOV antibodies. The primates were then back-challenged with the wild type Ebola virus and survived. This potentially creates a prospect for a future vaccine development.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Woolsey C, Menicucci AR, Cross RW, Luthra P, Agans KN, Borisevich V, Geisbert JB, Mire CE, Fenton KA, Jankeel A, Anand S, Ebihara H, Geisbert TW, Messaoudi I, Basler CF | display-authors = 6 | title = A VP35 Mutant Ebola Virus Lacks Virulence but Can Elicit Protective Immunity to Wild-Type Virus Challenge | language = English | journal = Cell Reports | volume = 28 | issue = 12 | pages = 3032\u201346.e6 | date = September 2019 | pmid = 31533029 | pmc = 6886687 | doi = 10.1016/j.celrep.2019.08.047 | url = https://www.cell.com/cell-reports/abstract/S2211-1247(19)31095-2 }}</ref>\n\n== Clinical trials in West Africa ==\nIn January 2015,  Marie-Paule Kieny, the [[World Health Organization]]'s (WHO) assistant director-general of health systems and innovation, announced that the vaccines cAd3-EBO Z and VSV-EBOV had demonstrated acceptable safety profiles during early testing and would soon progress to large-scale trials in Liberia, Sierra Leone and Guinea. The trials would involve up to 27,000 people and comprise 3 groups \u2013 members of the first two groups would receive the two candidate vaccines, while the third group will receive a [[placebo]].<ref>{{cite web|title=UK leads promising Ebola vaccine trial Pharmaceutical company looking into largescale manufacturing if trials are successful|url=https://arstechnica.com/science/2015/01/uk-leads-promising-ebola-vaccine-trial/|work=[[Ars Technica]]|access-date=10 January 2015}}</ref>  Both vaccines have since successfully completed the [[Phases of clinical research|Phase 2]] studies.  The large scale [[Phases of clinical research|Phase 3]] studies have begun {{as of|April 2015|lc=yes}}, in Liberia and Sierra Leone,<ref name=\"NIHPR\"/><ref name=\"CDCPR\"/> and in Guinea in March 2016.<ref name=\"who.int\"/>\n\nIn addition, a medical anthropologist at [[Universit\u00e9 de Montr\u00e9al]], had been working in Guinea and raised further questions about safety in the ring trial after spending time in April at one of the Ebola treatment units where trial participants are taken if they become ill, the centre in Coyah, about 50{{nbsp}}km from the capital of Conakry.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Russia)|Russian Foreign Ministry]] announced in 2016, the intention to conduct field trials of two Russian vaccines involving 2000 people.<ref name=\"iol.co.za\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.iol.co.za/news/world/russia-to-fund-ebola-vaccine-trials-1998046|title=Russia to fund Ebola vaccine trials|access-date=2017-09-14}}</ref> According to local media reports, the Guinean government authorized the commencement of the trials on 9 August 2017, at the [[Rusal]]-built Research and Diagnostic Center of Epidemiology and Microbiology in [[Kindia Region|Kindia]]. The trials were slated to continue until 2018.<ref name=\"iol.co.za\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.afrique-sur7.fr/60736/guinee-vaccin-trouve-teste-contre-virus-ebola/|title=Guin\u00e9e: un vaccin trouv\u00e9 et test\u00e9 contre le virus Ebola \u2013 Afrique Sur 7 : actualit\u00e9 de notre Afrique et du monde|website=www.afrique-sur7.fr|language=fr|access-date=2017-09-14}}</ref> As of October 2019, Russia licensed the vaccine and was reportedly ready to ship vaccine to Africa.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tass.com/science/1084757|title=Russia ready to supply Ebola vaccine to Africa |date=|website=TASS|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-01}}</ref>\n\n==U.S. national stockpile==\nIn 2014, [[Credit Suisse]] estimated that the U.S. government will provide over $1{{nbsp}}billion in contracts to companies to develop medicine and vaccines for Ebola virus disease.<ref name = \"CNN 20141028\">{{Cite news | url = http://money.cnn.com/2014/10/28/news/companies/ebola-drug-billion/ | title = Ebola: The making of a $1 billion drug | last = Rooney | first = Ben | name-list-format = vanc | date = 28 October 2014 | work = [[CNN]] | access-date = 19 November 2014}}</ref> Congress passed a law in 2004, that funds a national stockpile of vaccines and medicine for possible outbreaks of disease.<ref name = \"CNN 20141028\" /> A number of companies were expected to develop Ebola vaccines: [[GlaxoSmithKline]], [[NewLink Genetics]], [[Johnson & Johnson]] and [[Bavarian Nordic]].<ref name = \"CNN 20141028\" /> Another company, [[Emergent BioSolutions]], was a contestant for manufacturing new doses of [[ZMapp]],{{cn|date=November 2019}} a drug for Ebola virus disease treatment originally developed by [[Mapp Biopharmaceutical]].<ref>{{Cite news | url = http://www.bizjournals.com/baltimore/news/2014/10/20/emergent-biosolutions-among-three-under.html | title = Emergent BioSolutions among three under consideration for Ebola drug manufacturing | last = Gantz | first = Sarah | name-list-format = vanc | date = 20 October 2014 | work = [[Baltimore Business Journal]] | access-date = 13 November 2014}}</ref> Supplies of ZMapp ran out in August 2014.<ref>{{cite news | title = Ebola test drug's supply 'exhausted' after shipments to Africa, U.S. company says | first1 = Lenny | last1 = Bernstein | first2 = Brady | last2 = Dennis | website = [[The Washington Post]] | name-list-format = vanc | date = 11 August 2014 | url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/health-science/ebola-test-drugs-supply-exhausted-after-shipments-to-africa-us-company-says/2014/08/11/020cefc0-2199-11e4-958c-268a320a60ce_story.html | access-date = 17 November 2019 }}</ref> In September 2014, the [[Biomedical Advanced Research and Development Authority]] (BARDA) entered into a multimillion-dollar contract with Mapp Biopharmaceutical to accelerate the development of ZMapp.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = McCarthy M | title = US signs contract with ZMapp maker to accelerate development of the Ebola drug | journal = BMJ | volume = 349 | issue = sep04 10 | pages = g5488 | date = September 2014 | pmid = 25189475 | doi = 10.1136/bmj.g5488 }}</ref> Additional contracts were signed in 2017.<ref>{{cite press release | title=MappBio Announces Contracts with BARDA for ZMapp and Additional Filovirus Medical Countermeasures | publisher=[[Mapp Biopharmaceutical]] | date=29 September 2017 | url=https://mappbio.com/mappbio-announces-contracts-barda-zmapptm-additional-filovirus-medical-countermeasures/ | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191117040246/https://mappbio.com/mappbio-announces-contracts-barda-zmapptm-additional-filovirus-medical-countermeasures/ | archive-date=17 November 2019 | url-status=live | access-date=16 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Ebola virus disease]]\n* [[Ebola virus disease treatment research]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|32em}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n{{refbegin|32em}}\n* {{cite journal | vauthors = Farooq F, Beck K, Paolino KM, Phillips R, Waters NC, Regules JA, Bergmann-Leitner ES | title = Circulating follicular T helper cells and cytokine profile in humans following vaccination with the rVSV-ZEBOV Ebola vaccine | journal = Scientific Reports | volume = 6 | pages = 27944 | date = June 2016 | pmid = 27323685 | pmc = 4914957 | doi = 10.1038/srep27944 | bibcode = 2016NatSR...627944F }}\n* {{cite journal | vauthors = Sullivan N, Yang ZY, Nabel GJ | title = Ebola virus pathogenesis: implications for vaccines and therapies | journal = Journal of Virology | volume = 77 | issue = 18 | pages = 9733\u20137 | date = September 2003 | pmid = 12941881 | pmc = 224575 | doi = 10.1128/JVI.77.18.9733-9737.2003 }}\n* {{cite journal | vauthors = Diakite I, Mooring EQ, Vel\u00e1squez GE, Murray MB | title = Novel Ordered Stepped-Wedge Cluster Trial Designs for Detecting Ebola Vaccine Efficacy Using a Spatially Structured Mathematical Model | journal = PLOS Neglected Tropical Diseases | volume = 10 | issue = 8 | pages = e0004866 | date = August 2016 | pmid = 27509037 | pmc = 4979980 | doi = 10.1371/journal.pntd.0004866 }}\n* {{cite journal | vauthors = Cazares LH, Ward MD, Bruegge