{"title_page": "Wisden Leading Woman Cricketer in the World", "text_new": "{{DISPLAYTITLE:''Wisden'' Leading Woman Cricketer in the World}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\nThe '''''Wisden'' Leading Woman Cricketer in the World''' is an annual [[cricket]] award selected by the editor of ''[[Wisden Cricketers' Almanack]]''. It was established in 2015,<ref>{{Cite web | url = https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2015/apr/08/wisden-leading-woman-cricketer-in-the-world-award-meg-lanninghttps://www.theguardian.com/sport/2015/apr/08/wisden-leading-woman-cricketer-in-the-world-award-meg-lanning | work = The Guardian | title = Wisden\u2019s women cricketer award is testament to how far the game has come | first = Heather | last = Knight | authorlink = Heather Knight (cricketer) | accessdate = 14 August 2016 | date = 8 April 2015}}</ref> to select the best female cricketer based upon their performances anywhere in the world in the previous calendar year.<ref name=bloom>{{Cite web | url = http://www.bloomsbury.com/uk/special-interest/wisden/wisden-honours/leading-woman-cricketer-in-the-world/ | publisher = Bloomsbury | title = Leading Woman Cricketer in the World | accessdate = 14 August 2016}}</ref>  Prior to the establishment of this dedicated award, women were also eligible for inclusion in ''[[Wisden Cricketers' Almanack|Wisden]]''{{'s}} [[Wisden Cricketers of the Year|Cricketers of the Year]]; two were selected, England's [[Claire Taylor]] in 2009 and [[Charlotte Edwards]] in 2014.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://content-www.cricinfo.com/wisdenalmanack/content/current/story/209422.html | title = Wisden's Five Cricketers of the Year | work = [[Wisden Cricketers' Almanack]] | accessdate =14 August 2016 }}</ref>\n\nThe inaugural recipient of the  ''Wisden'' Leading Woman Cricketer in the World was [[Australia women's national cricket team|Australian international cricketer]] [[Meg Lanning]].<ref name=lanning>{{Cite web | url = http://www.abc.net.au/news/2015-04-08/lanning-wins-inaugural-wisen-women27s-cricket-award/6379192 | publisher = [[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]] | title = Australia's Meg Lanning named Wisden's Leading Woman Cricketer in the World | date = 8 April 2015 | accessdate = 14 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe most recent awardee is [[Australia women's national cricket team|Australia]]'s [[Ellyse Perry]].\n\n==Winners==\n{|class=\"sortable wikitable\"\n|-\n!scope=\"col\" | Year\n!scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\"| Image\n!scope=\"col\" | Winner\n!scope=\"col\" | Nationality\n!scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\"| Notes\n!scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | {{abbr|Ref(s)|References}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" | 2014\n| [[File:2016\u201317 WBBL PS v MS 17-01-15 Lanning (01).jpg|frameless|100px]]\n| {{sortname|Meg|Lanning}}\n| [[Australia women's national cricket team|Australia]]\n| [[ICC Awards#2014 Awards|T20I Women's Cricketer of the Year (2014)]]<br>Youngest player to captain Australia\n| <ref name=bloom/><ref name=lanning/>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" | 2015\n| [[File:2016\u201317 WBBL ST v PS 17-01-21 Bates (06).jpg |frameless|100px]]\n| {{sortname|Suzie|Bates}}\n| [[New Zealand women's national cricket team|New Zealand]]\n| Player of the Tournament at the [[2013 Women's Cricket World Cup|2013 World Cup]] <br> [[ICC Awards#2014 Awards|T20I Women's Cricketer of the Year (2013)]]<br> Captain of both the [[One Day International]] and [[Twenty20 International]] teams since 2012\n| <ref>{{Cite web | url = http://www.espncricinfo.com/wisdenalmanack/content/story/997083.html | work = ESPNcricinfo | accessdate = 14 August 2016 | title = Suzie Bates | first = Raf | last= Nicholson}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url = http://www.skysports.com/cricket/news/31996/10241508/new-zealand-skipper-suzie-bates-named-worlds-leading-female-cricketer | publisher = [[Sky Sports]] | accessdate = 14 August 2016 | first = Dev |last = Trehan | title = New Zealand skipper Suzie Bates named world's leading female cricketer }}<